<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Shakes Tokyo Islands  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A moderately strong earthquake shook a string of
volcanic islands off Tokyo on Sunday, the Meteorological Agency
said. Police reported no damage or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The quake, with a preliminary magnitude of 5, was centered
beneath the seabed near the islands of Niijima and Kozushima and
struck just after noon local time, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no danger of undersea waves triggered by volcanic
activity or earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was most strongly felt on the island of Shikinejima,
about 93 miles south of Tokyo. The island is near Niijima and
Kozushima. There were no reports of damage on any of the islands.
</P>
<P>
   A quake of magnitude 5 can cause damage to homes if it occurs in
a residential area.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's quake was among thousands that have hit the small
islands of the Izu islands chain in recent weeks. On July 1, a
magnitude 6.4 earthquake killed a man on Kozushima.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most earthquake-prone nations as it
sits atop four tectonic plates, slabs of land that move across the
earth's surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
