<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese River Dries up in Drought  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A persisting drought has dried up one of China's
major rivers for a month, threatening the economy of the northeast,
the state-run China Youth Daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Songhua River ran dry June 19 in Zhaoyuan county, a marshy
stretch of farmland 70 miles west of Harbin, capital of
Heilongjiang province, the newspaper said. It added that people can
now cross the river by foot.
</P>
<P>
   The report blamed drought. Since the start of what is usually
the summer rainy season in May, Heilongjiang has seen high
temperatures and rainfall that has been a paltry 70 percent less
than usual, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Across northern China, drought this year already has destroyed
35 million acres of crops and left at least 16.2 million people
short of water.
</P>
<P>
   The Songhua feeds one of China's richest grain-growing regions
and a strip of heavily industrialized cities. Two years ago, amid
China's worst flooding in a half-century, the Songhua inundated
surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>
   A water-use planning expert for the province, Wang Xinde, warned
that the river's drying up will have disastrous consequences for
the lives and livelihoods of 40 million people in the Songhua
basin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
