<DOCNO> APW20000723.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-8 Leaders Focus On Third World  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGO, Okinawa (AP) -- Leaders of the world's major industrialized
nations, hoping to stem a growing backlash against globalization,
pledged Sunday at their annual economic summit to do more to
provide schooling, health care and food to the poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
   In a communique issued at the conclusion of their three-day
summit, the leaders cited ''unprecedented economic progress'' by
many world nations and agreed that more must be done to spread that
prosperity to poorer nations. ''The 21st century must be a century
of prosperity for all,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   They said their countries must work harder to relieve the debt
burden of developing nations. ''We must for our part promote more
responsible lending and borrowing practices to ensure that (poor
countries) will not again be burdened by unsupportable debt,'' the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, whose country agreed to
restructure $4 billion of Russia's debt, suggested that wealthy
nations hold back demands for poorer countries to pay off their
loans. ''It would be better to put the money in health and
education systems in these countries,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Okinawa meeting was the first ''development summit'' for the
Group of Eight -- leaders of the seven richest industrialized
nations and Russia, and the last G-8 meeting for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced that the United States will send $300 million
in surplus farm crops to provide school lunches in the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think we can increase by millions and millions (the number
of children in school) just by telling these children and their
parents we will give them one hot meal,'' Clinton said before the
final session of world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The president cut short his schedule in Okinawa to hurry home to
another summit -- the Mideast peace talks that were continuing in
his absence at Camp David, Md. Before boarding Air Force One,
Clinton went over to quickly shake hands with a crowd of
well-wishers waiting in a heavy rain to watch his departure from
Kadena Air Base.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori, this year's G-8 summit
host, said wealthy nations had an obligation to break the ''vicious
cycle'' of poverty and disease faced by poor nations. But Mori
declined to say whether Japan would provide funding for building
information technology infrastructure in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Information technology) is an area that needs to progress in
the private sector. The government really should be complementary''
in its role, Mori said.
</P>
<P>
   In their communique, they put forth a laundry list of objectives
to make sure that the economic benefits from an increasingly
interconnected world are shared more widely.
</P>
<P>
   The eight countries set a goal of universal primary education
for all the world's children by 2015, and gender equality in
schools by 2005. Currently, 100 million children in developing
nations are not in school.
</P>
<P>
   They also vowed to reduce by the year 2010 the number of
HIV-infected young people by 25 percent, tuberculosis deaths by 50
percent, and the burden of diseases associated with malaria by 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a spokesman for U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
issued a statement expressing disappointment that the leaders did
not address debt relief more aggressively, noting that so far,
relief had been extended to only nine of 41 extremely poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where there is agreement in principle that debt relief is
essential, and where delays have a profoundly negative impact on
the lives of poor people, clearly more must be done,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But Roman Prodi, president of the European Commission, said
Annan's statement was unfair. ''He expressed his disappointment
before we even discussed the problem in Okinawa,'' Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
   The summit did not resolve differences between North America and
Europe over the risks of genetically modified foods, French
President Jacques Chirac said Sunday. He noted that the United
States and Canada generally think such food is not dangerous, while
European and Japanese leaders are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   The differences were apparent in the joint communique issued at
the end of the three-day summit, which gave nods to both points of
view in vague language.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said he spoke for the leaders
of Japan, Germany, France, Canada, Italy and Russia in praising
Clinton's efforts for global stability over the past eight years.
Clinton leaves office in six months and will not attend another G-8
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Blair also answered critics from outside the summit, who have
complained that the G-8 summit failed to do enough for poor
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''For many who work hard in the developing world, progress is
often agonizingly slow,'' Blair said. ''But we have made some
significant steps,'' in helping poorer nations at this session.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides insisted that the discussions had been
productive in countering the attacks from thousands of
demonstrators who marched in the streets of Seattle last December
and in Washington in April to protest that globalization helps the
wealthy nations and international corporations at the expense of
the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government brought in 20,000 police officers to
provide security during the summit on the island nation in the
Pacific, and there were no disruptions by protesters. On Thursday,
tens of thousands of peaceful demonstrators protested against the
massive U.S. military presence on the island, but the streets were
quiet after Clinton arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the initiatives put forth by the leaders featured grand
aims with little financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders agreed to create a digital opportunity task force,
or ''dot force,'' to expand Internet access and make it more
affordable in developing nations. They also said governments should
avoid regulating information technology too tightly, and they
pledged protections for intellectual property rights in cyberspace.
A report on this effort is to be presented at next year's G-8
summit in Genoa, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee 2000, a religious-based coalition that campaigns for
debt forgiveness, said the summit's emphasis on closing the
''digital divide'' was a puzzling goal in a world where poor
countries can't supply electricity or running water to millions and
starvation is an ever-present threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't eat computers, said Jubilee 2000 coordinator Kewesi
Owusu. ''People are dying.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department site on the summit:
http://www.state.gov/www/issues/economic/summit/g8--2000--index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
