<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Rocks Sumatra  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A strong earthquake with a magnitude
of 5.5 shook Indonesia's Sumatra island Sunday, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Armyn Paimin, an official with the Meteorological and Geophysics
Agency, was quoted by the official Antara news agency as saying
that there were no immediate reports of damage or casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Paimin said the temblor hit at 3:55 a.m. local time, 20 miles
beneath the Indian Ocean, and 270 miles northwest of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   He said the quake was worst felt in the town of Bengkulu, where
a 7.9 magnitude temblor on June 4 killed about 100 people and left
thousands homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's quake was the latest in a series of seismic upheavals
that have rocked the world's largest archipelagic nation in the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia is prone to earthquakes because of its location on the
Pacific ''Ring of Fire'' -- a line of volcanically active areas
stretching from the western coast of the Americas across to Japan,
Southeast Asia and the South Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
