<HEADLINE> Bergen County hospital: Massages reduce pain for chronically ill  </HEADLINE>
By NINA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Staff and patients at a Bergen County
hospital agree: A program there offering massages to the
chronically ill has reduced their anxiety and dependence on
painkillers and helped them sleep better.
</P>
<P>
   A long-term care unit at Bergen Regional Medical Center is
working with a Westwood massage school as part of a pilot program
offering the rubdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not as preoccupied with their health complaints,''
April Judge, the nurse in charge of the unit, said of her patients.
''You see more smiles on their faces. They just seem happier.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 60-bed unit is filled with people who have multiple
sclerosis, are recovering from a stroke or are suffering from some
other debilitating illness. Many are wheelchair-bound or bedridden.
Some of the MS patients have been there almost two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like a new person,'' said Helen Christiano, 65, of
Lodi. The retired credit manager is learning to walk again after a
stroke. She has been hospitalized for 18 months while her husband
waits at home for her to recover. ''This relaxes me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Healing Hands Institute for Massage Therapy, which offers a
certification in hospital-based massage therapy, sends students to
the hospital once a week as part of their training. They give
massages free of charge to about 20 patients who take pain
medication daily.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials say the partnership with the school is the
first of its kind in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Medical massage is an important addition to the treatment (of
long-term care patients), especially as it relates to pain
management in the geriatric population,'' said Fred S. Sganga,
president and CEO of Bergen Regional Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Sganga hopes to make the massages a permanent fixture in the
hospital's entire long-term care division, which has 691 beds in a
nursing home setting.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, restful rubdowns that are not part of a physical
therapy program are ''not well received'' by most insurers, Sganga
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians hope that will change soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should be incorporating complementary medicine into
conventional medicine. That's the wave of the future,'' said Dr.
Louis Teichholz, medical director for complementary medicine at
Hackensack University Medical Center. The center runs two spas for
public and patient use.
</P>
<P>
   Spa services are not covered by insurance, he said, and unlike
the Bergen program, patients must pay.
</P>
<P>
   Teichholz, who is also chief of cardiology at Hackensack, said
massage therapy relaxes muscles and reduces stress, which is
important because stress weakens the immune system and slows
healing.
</P>
<P>
   Massages also reduce swelling, increase blood flow and
flexibility, and restore tone to flaccid muscles, proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal is to show that this works well enough so insurance
companies eventually pay for it,'' Teichholz said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is one of 29 states that require message therapists
to be licensed. Therapists must complete, on average, 500 hours of
training before receiving certification, according to the American
Message Therapy Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
