<HEADLINE> Philippine Hostage Hopes Rise  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Flying his plane over the
Philippine island of Jolo, Malaysian pilot Fong Shaufah focused his
gaze on a chain of forested mountains, wondering where Muslim
guerrillas are holding his son and dozens of other hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Fong, who works for a Malaysian air charter company, was hired
to fly Malaysian officials to the Philippines to monitor
negotiations for the release of his son, Ken, and other hostages
held by separatist Abu Sayyaf rebels, some for as long as four
months.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he flew with high hopes to Jolo to pick up four
Malaysian hostages freed by the rebels. Unfortunately, his son
wasn't among them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a flurry of releases this past week has rekindled hopes
among the captives' relatives that the hostage standoff is nearing
an end.
</P>
<P>
   ''For us, the worst time was the first week,'' Fong said. ''We
didn't know where they were and we didn't know whether they were
dead or alive. Now, there is much better hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken was among 21 people taken hostage April 23 at Malaysia's
Sipadan diving resort and brought to the Philippines by boat. Abu
Sayyaf guerrillas later kidnapped 13 Filipino Christian evangelists
and three French TV journalists. A separate armed group on Jolo is
believed to be holding a German reporter for Der Spiegel magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Following the latest releases, the groups were believed to be
holding six French people, three Germans, two Finns, two South
Africans, three Malaysians and 15 Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, the rebels released their first European hostage,
Renate Wallert of Germany. On Thursday, they released the son of a
Philippine government soldier who was killed in a clash with the
guerrillas, and on Friday they freed two Filipino teachers and the
four Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
   Government negotiators called the releases a breakthrough that
would lead to the rapid freedom of the other hostages.
</P>
<P>
   But the optimism has been tempered by growing disputes among the
rebel leaders over their demands and the division of ransom
payments. Tensions also erupted Thursday within the government
negotiating team: Chief negotiator Robert Aventajado accused Lee
Peng Wee, a former presidential adviser with business interests in
Malaysia, of violating instructions and endangering the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Since the hostage crisis began, the Philippines' government has
been at a loss on how to resolve the standoff, particularly because
of the large number of foreigners being held.
</P>
<P>
   Government negotiators initially tried to intimidate the rebels
by having soldiers encircle their hinterland camp on Jolo. That led
to clashes and warnings from foreign governments against employing
force.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to use the military, the government then focused on
negotiations. But bargaining with the Abu Sayyaf commanders has
proved difficult because of the rebels' loose chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Abu Sayyaf have five different leaders, so it takes a
while to get their concurrence,'' Aventajado said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While some rebel commanders have emphasized political demands,
including a separate Islamic nation and improved treatment of
Filipinos living in neighboring Malaysia, another faction is mainly
interested in money and is demanding $1 million for each European
hostage, negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippines has a no-ransom policy, and President Joseph
Estrada has urged the rebels to accept offers of development
projects from countries like Libya, Malaysia and Germany. However,
emissaries working for the government negotiators reported that
ransoms were covertly paid to secure the release of the Malaysians
and the German woman.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Sayyaf commanders Ghalib Andang and Mujib Susukan, who have
direct custody of the hostages, are demanding $1 million for each
hostage as well as an orange plantation for farmers on Jolo and
other efforts to create jobs, negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappings will surely keep investors and tourists away
from Jolo for a long time. But local politicians say the crisis has
focused attention on the island's wrenching poverty, and they hope
it will prod the government to spend on development projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''The islands, the blue waters, they are fantastic,'' Fong said.
''But unless the problems are solved, nobody will come to visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong said he hadn't abandoned hope for the release of his son.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm still hopeful,'' he said. ''I'm still waiting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 1219 </TRAILER>
