<HEADLINE> Authorities see new wave of counterfeit cash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - A lot of people in Connecticut have been
making money on computers. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities estimate about $400,000 in computer-generated
counterfeit cash hit the state last year and a string of recent
cases has caught their attention.
</P>
<P>
   High-quality, low-cost color printers have bred a new type of
computer-savvy counterfeiter. They use off-the-shelf computers,
image scanners and printers to generate thousands in fake bills
every year. About half of the counterfeit bills found in
Connecticut are now computer-generated, said Mark Enright of the
U.S. Secret Service in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Enright's office, founded during the Civil War to thwart
counterfeiters, is responsible for investigating the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-assisted counterfeiting isn't new. But the problem has
been steadily worsening over the last decade, Enright said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Fourth of July, a pair of Hartford men were arrested at
Lake Compounce amusement park in Bristol carrying hundreds of
dollars in fake $10 bills. Police believe they changed over $400 at
the park before being caught.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a Meriden man pleaded guilty to manufacturing
more than $3,000 in phony dough on his home computer. He faces up
to 15 years in prison and a $250,000 fine. In April, a Southington
man was charged with forgery for passing fake money at a service
station.
</P>
<P>
   Cases have also been reported in New Britain, Middletown and in
Plainville, where police say there were six incidents in the last
three months.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clerks and business managers have to be very careful handling
cash,'' said Plainville police Lt. Brian Mullins.
</P>
<P>
   Phony bills found in the area were all copies of the old-style
currency in denominations of ten, five, and even one dollar. New
bill designs contain several hard-to-replicate features.
</P>
<P>
   The fakes can look real, but they never feel quite right. There
is nothing available on the open market to replicate the paper used
in genuine greenbacks, Enright said
</P>
<P>
   ''Usually, the paper is a dead giveaway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Criminals usually try to pass the money at busy stores where
clerks don't have time to carefully look at every bill. They pass a
counterfeit and then take the change in real bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a place like Lake Compounce where every two feet is a
concession stand or a game ... it's easy to pass it,'' Enright
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service makes about 25 arrests a year in Connecticut,
Enright said. The agency is currently investigating several
counterfeiting rings in Hartford, New Haven, and Fairfield
Counties, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-23-00 1314 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000723.0029 </DOCNO>
