<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In the 1990s, 64 companies shut down after receiving state aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - More than 60 companies which received aid
from the Connecticut Development Authority during the 1990s have
since closed, an investigation by The Sunday Republican shows.
</P>
<P>
   According to records obtained by the paper, the Connecticut
Development Authority gave loans and loan guarantees to 881
companies to expand or create new jobs between July 1, 1991, and
June 30, 1999. Of those, 64 had gone out of business or left the
state by June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, those 64 companies received $36 million in CDA loans
and bank loan guarantees, and took 1,275 jobs with them.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies receiving loans designed to boost employment did
not fail, but cut more than 5,000 jobs during that same time frame.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, records show the CDA lent $28 million to at least 20
companies that went on to fail, including $14 million to the
Hartford Whalers hockey team, which ended up moving its 109 jobs to
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   CDA Executive Director Tony Roberto said policies have since
been put in place to close loopholes that allowed companies to
escape penalties despite failing to meet employment requirements
for their loans.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto said the CDA, a public-private agency, gave money more
liberally in the early 1990s to try to stem the rising tide of
layoffs and red ink Connecticut businesses were facing at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the job losses, the 881 companies receiving aid now have
1,451 more jobs than they had in 1991. Roberto said 8,341 new jobs
have been created at companies that haven't lost any employees.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that the CDA turned a profit the last two
years, and the Legislature continues to renew the agency's mandate
to take risks on behalf of business, whether through guarantees or
direct loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-23-00 1314 </TRAILER>
