<DOCNO> APW20000723.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stretch of Interstate 95 is one of most deadly in state  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   When Interstate 95 was built in the 1950s, the state
considered
it a pathway to prosperity for the shoreline cities through which
it wound.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, I-95 is considered treacherous, having claimed 130 lives
from 1993 to 1998 and six already this year.
</P>
<P>
   How did the road get so bad? State leaders will focus on the
issue, and ways to resolve it, during a statewide transportation
summit Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   I-95 opened Jan. 2, 1958 with 40,000 cars a day traveling the
road. Engineers predicted traffic would increase to 60,000 cars a
day by 1974 and the road would have to be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   The predictions rang true, but it wasn't until the Mianus River
Bridge in Greenwich collapsed in 1983 - killing three people - that
major repairs began. Even now, despite efforts by the state
Department of Transportation to relieve congestion, nearly all
construction efforts have gone into repairs and safety
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 160,000 cars a day pass through Bridgeport on I-95,
the DOT says.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has changed from bad to worse because there's just so much
on so little pavement,'' veteran radio traffic reporter Morgan
Kaolian told the Connecticut Post. ''The truckers have pretty much
taken over.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the latest year for which statistics are available,
there were 667 tractor-trailer accidents in the 111.6 miles between
the New York state line and Stonington - the majority of them on
the stretch from Greenwich to New Haven. In both 1998 and 1997, 22
people were killed in collisions on I-95 and 17 died in 1996,
according to the DOT.
</P>
<P>
   Kaolian believes that even doubling the six lanes of I-95 would
not alleviate the traffic crunch, particularly from local drivers
who hop on I-95 for a couple of exits. Bringing back the
controversial tolls and closing some exit ramps would reduce
traffic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Gov. John G. Rowland, say the number of trucks
which travel the highway and crowd rest stations and ramps when
they park for breaks has to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's scary,'' said Rowland, who admitted the situation is not
an easy one to solve. ''You can't wake up tomorrow and say 'Trucks,
don't come.'''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Martinez, chief of planning for the DOT, said truck
accidents along I-95 haven't substantially increased in recent
years. Trucks make up about 11 percent of the traffic and an equal
percentage of the accidents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers blame aggressive and inattentive motorists and
seemingly never-ending road construction.
</P>
<P>
   ''This part of the country is not truck driver-friendly,'' said
Donnie Phelps, of Clarksville, Tenn. ''I have to watch out for the
other guy more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   At the September summit, scheduled to be held in Hartford,
lawmakers plan to review technology and travel alternatives
available to improve all the state's roads. But I-95 will be a
focus.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said video cameras that allow state police to monitor
traffic and accidents on I-95 from Greenwich to New Haven have been
a positive advance. State Speaker of the House Moira Lyons,
D-Stamford, though, said weigh stations meant to ensure trucks meet
size and safety regulations are underused.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Jacqueline Cocco, a Bridgeport Democrat who co-chairs
the Legislature's Transportation Committee, said boosting the use
of public transportation could be the key.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-23-00 1314 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000723.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grassroots effort to restore historic, abandoned cemeteries  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOLUNTOWN, Conn. (AP) - Somebody must have thought a lot of Joel
Kinne.
</P>
<P>
   When he died in 1845 at the age of 53, a handsome, intricately
carved headstone was prepared for him. His epitaph reads: ''The
tall, the wise, the reverend head, shall lie as low as ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people think about him anymore. The cemetery where Kinne
lies has been abandoned, his grave decorated with nothing but pine
cones and low-bush blueberries in the woods behind a state
transportation depot.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his neighbors in the afterlife fared worse: headstones
tilt every which way, and many lie on the ground or under it,
covered by soil and greenery and decades of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Such small cemeteries dot the woodlands and subdivisions of
Connecticut like milestones to a map of state history, where
lopsided, forgotten tombstones become buried treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The sorry state of such cemeteries is being reversed in many
eastern Connecticut towns, driven by civic pride and the
Internet-fueled interest in genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the feeling is, the dead don't vote and they don't pay
taxes, so nobody cares about them,'' said Rusty Godino, a volunteer
on Ledyard's Cemetery Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ledyard has tried to reverse the trend with an adopt-a-cemetery
program. Groups, scout packs and families agree to care for a
cemetery by mowing grass and raking leaves. They keep watch for
vandals and report any serious problem, like broken tombstones or
crumbling walls.
</P>
<P>
   Other towns are trying to replicate Ledyard's program.
</P>
<P>
   In Voluntown, municipal workers are enlisted to clean out the
brush and make the cemeteries look respectable. Such work was
recently done where Kinne lies and efforts are underway to restore
the old burial ground.
</P>
<P>
   Some families have taken on cemetery restoration as a learning
project.
</P>
<P>
   Iva Arpin, of Griswold, and her family have raised stones,
gently cleaned them and catalogued the information they displayed.
One cemetery they fixed up was a party place for teen-agers; the
area was strewn with bottles and litter.
</P>
<P>
   The experience fueled an interest in American history in her
children and taught them respect, Arpin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a family researcher,'' Arpin said. ''I decided I wanted to
do something to make people aware of their history.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is really sure how many cemeteries are in Connecticut. A
Works Progress Administration project in the 1930s under Charles R.
Hale found 2,269 cemeteries, including long-abandoned plots under
reservoirs and state highways.
</P>
<P>
   But some cemeteries and graves catalogued by Hale have
disappeared and others have been found that the project did not
uncover, said Ruth Shapleigh-Brown, executive director of the
Connecticut Gravestone Network.
</P>
<P>
   The Hale Collection of tombstone inscriptions is on file at the
Connecticut State Library for the use of people interested in
genealogy, or the study of family descent.
</P>
<P>
   Genealogy interest has grown as baby boomers age and thanks to
the Internet, which provides information on free and easy-to-use
sites, Shapleigh-Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   About three-quarters of the members of the Gravestone Network
joined the effort to preserve and restore cemeteries because of
their genealogy interest.
</P>
<P>
   Caring for the cemeteries is mostly a volunteer job. Many old
cemeteries still have associations that were formed decades ago to
see to the upkeep of the dead, but as cemeteries got full and the
money ran out the associations dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows towns to take over the upkeep of abandoned
burial grounds, but the state does not require towns to spend any
money on the plots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything lacks time, staffing, money,'' Shapleigh-Brown
said. ''I'd say most towns just abandon their old cemetery sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten graves can create problems for developers. As soon as
a backhoe uncovers a skeleton or grave, work must stop while the
police are consulted, said state archaeologist Nick Bellantoni.
</P>
<P>
   One such finding generated a stir in Griswold about 10 years
ago, when a forgotten burial site was found during a mining
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The finding became known as the ''Griswold vampire legend,''
although Bellantoni said the facts have nothing to do with the
vampires of movie fame.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it was fear of tuberculosis that led people in the early
19th century to dig up the bones of their ancestors and rearrange
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some families believed the disease was transmitted from
deceased family members. They thought the dead were undead, and
could leave the housing of their grave and be mischievous - spread
the disease to living family members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that thighbones of a skeleton had been removed
and crossed over the chest, and a head that had been removed was
placed on the chest. Other evidence showed the heart was removed.
</P>
<P>
   The finding provided a ''unique insight'' into the stress and
fear of disease in the 1820s and 1830s, Bellantoni said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped the grass-roots efforts to find, catalog,
research and preserve cemeteries will lead to a protection policy
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless that kind of research is done, nobody's going to know
what's there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Gravestone Network:
http://members.aol.com/ctgravenet/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut State Library: www.cslib.org
</P>
</TEXT>
