<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troopers say state's left-lane law will be enforced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GIBSONIA, Pa. (AP) - Warnings issued to left-lane drivers on the
Pennsylvania Turnpike are running out, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   From January to March this year, 220 motorists were cited for
hogging the left lane on the Pennsylvania Turnpike, police said.
The citations stem from a new state law adopted in December that
prohibits motorists from driving in the left lane of limited-access
highways except when passing other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're issued a lot of warnings and now we're citing drivers,''
said state police Cpl. Ahmed Shareef of Gibsonia north of
Pittsburgh in Butler County. ''The law seems pretty cut and dry,
although a lot of people say they never heard about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that if a motorist driving in the left lane blocks the
regular flow of traffic and fails to merge right after a trooper
has trailed him or her for three miles, the motorist can expect a
ticket. The fine is $25, but can rise to $100 with court costs and
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the law is vague, and roadways lack signs warning
drivers that too much time in the left lane is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone told me this is what they were cited for, I'd say,
'You must be mistaken,''' said Pittsburgh attorney Melissa Owen.
''It definitely has some problems with the way it reads now.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen and Shawn Stephenson, a suburban Pittsburgh attorney
specializing in motor vehicle law, said the law doesn't say how
long a motorist can be in the left lane after passing another
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The law also doesn't account for cars that move left to make
room for other cars merging onto a roadway or for driving in the
center lane of six-lane highways.
</P>
<P>
   The law says vehicles must be in the right lane except when
passing other vehicles or if they are directed into the left lane
by road signs, troopers or other traffic control devices. Drivers
are allowed to drive in the left lane up to two miles in
anticipation of turning left off a roadway.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Haver, a spokesman for AAA West Penn/West Virginia/South
Central Ohio, said his organization plans to lobby for changes in
the new law, mostly because of the lack of signs alerting drivers
to it. Other states with similar laws, such as New Jersey, have
erected such signs.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Myslewicz, a spokesman for the state Department of
Transportation, said PennDOT has no plans to put up any signs
regarding the left-lane law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
