<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hanover and Morristown bicker over who should deal with campsite  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HANOVER, N.J. (AP) - Two Morris County towns are exchanging
fighting words over who should deal with occupants of a campsite
along the west bank of the Whippany River.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years, Mike Macabee and several homeless
friends have lived quietly in an encampment in Hanover. However,
the property is owned by Morristown, which has a sewage treatment
plant there.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hanover officials accused Morristown of violating the
township's land-use laws by allowing the men to remain at the
wooded site.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our opinion, the Morristown sewer plant is not a legitimate
place for housing the homeless,'' Hanover Administrator Joseph
Giorgio told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Sunday's editions.
''They should be provided the services they deserve. Morristown has
to take some action to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Morristown officials replied that police in the neighboring town
are free to arrest the trespassers and deal with them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Macabee and his friends are caught in the middle of
the feud and say they don't understand why the towns will not leave
them alone.
</P>
<P>
   Macabee and the two other regulars keep the grounds neat.
They've set up three tents for sleeping and use a fourth tent for
storage. They even have a shower with heated water through a solar
bag they bought at a shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Would you rather have us bumming on the streets, or being
self-sufficient here?'' Macabee asked.
</P>
<P>
   Macabee does not have a regular job, but he picks up work
periodically to pay for his share of what the men need: food,
clothes, toiletries, camping equipment and beer.
</P>
<P>
   With the situation escalating, Macabee and the others say they
will have to find another place to set up camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're going to do what they're going to do, and I guess that
means we will have to go,'' Macabee said.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover officials said they have been trying unsuccessfully to
get Morristown to deal with the situation since officials
discovered the campsite while walking the east side of Whippany
River months ago.
</P>
<P>
   They first tried to get social service agencies to help find
places for the men, but the men at the campsite refused to accept
the help.
</P>
<P>
   So Hanover officials said they approached Morristown about
addressing the situation, but got tough after Morristown took no
action.
</P>
<P>
   Morristown Administrator Eric Maurer said the superintendent of
the sewer plant didn't see anyone living there when he walked the
property after receiving a phone call from Hanover officials.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer said he didn't hear any other complaints until last week
when he received a letter from Hanover accusing Morristown of
violating its land-use law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't ignore them, by any stretch of the imagination,''
Maurer said. ''If there are trespassers there, we'll have to call
police, and that would be their police.''
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio opposes intervention from law enforcement, and Hanover
police said they have not had any problems with the men living at
the campsite.
</P>
<P>
   ''These people didn't commit any crimes,'' Giorgio said. ''We
should not reduce a social problem to a police matter unless there
is a need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
