<HEADLINE> Time running out on pet bills in current Congress  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Sure, it's only July. But with presidential
and congressional campaigning about to take center stage, time is
running short to get bills through the 106th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Since this term began in 1999, New Jersey's 13 representatives
have cumulatively filed more than 380 pieces of legislation on such
varied topics as the flammability of children's sleepwear, import
duties on chocolate and the future of Atlantic striped bass.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, according to the Library of Congress Internet
site, Rep. Rob Andrews, D-Haddon Heights, led New Jersey lawmakers
with 100 bills or amendments proposed, while Rep. Frank LoBiondo,
R-Vineland, had offered just eight.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed bills are a guide to a legislator's priorities in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 15 proposed by Rep. Donald Payne, D-Newark, nine deal
with the topic of Africa, a continent that Payne has visited
numerous times. The House approved Payne's bill to congratulate the
people of Senegal for holding multiparty elections. But he was
unsuccessful in his effort to provide $15 million to the National
Democratic Alliance of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Rep. Marge Roukema, R-Ridgewood, has devoted many of
her 21 bills to the subject of finance, an appropriate interest for
the chairwoman of the House Banking subcommittee on financial
institutions. Most of the bills still await a first hearing,
although the House did pass her resolution encouraging the
international Financial Action Task Force on Money Laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Most legislative proposals go nowhere. In the two-year life of
the last Congress, members of the House introduced nearly 6,000
bills (which, if passed, become laws if signed by the president)
and resolutions (which do not carry the weight of law). Just over
1,000 were approved.
</P>
<P>
   Some bills seem to be introduced merely to make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Does Rep. Jim Saxton, R-Mount Holly, really expect the House to
name an ocean-dumping site the ''Albert Gore Jr. Mud Dump Site?''
That bill, which has had no hearings since Saxton introduced it in
January, is an attempt to blame the vice president for controversy
over a deal he helped broker to end dumping six miles off Sandy
Hook.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rush Holt of Pennington, a freshman Democrat, no doubt had
few illusions that the Republican-controlled House would pass his
bill to require licensing and registration of all handguns.
Introduced last November, the bill has not attracted a single
co-sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   And bills calling for amendments to the U.S. Constitution are
rarely adopted by Congress, but Andrews has proposed one to give
the president a line-item veto.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a glance - by no means comprehensive - at other
bills of New Jersey lawmakers and their status in the 106th
Congress:
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Pascrell, D-Paterson, has assembled support from 276
colleagues - more than half - for his bill to spend $5 billion over
five years in grants to local fire departments. A House committee
recently considered another Pascrell bill to require the government
to do a better job of informing veterans about available benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Rothman, D-Fair Lawn, won approval in May from the
House Judiciary Committee for a proposal to spend $60 million
annually for three years to help schools install metal detectors
and other security measures.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed into law a compromise version of
legislation sponsored by LoBiondo to stop deceptive practices of
some sweepstakes companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris Smith, R-Robbinsville, has gathered 199 co-sponsors
for a bill to boost surveillance and research of autism, 52
co-sponsors for a similar measure targeting Lyme disease and five
co-sponsors for a bill to increase research funding for Alzheimer's
disease while ensuring that Medicare fully covers treatment for
those with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews has proposed a grant program to encourage schools to
establish or expand prekindergarten programs.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton won House approval for his proposal to create a
commission to mark the 100th birthday of the National Wildlife
Refuge System.
</P>
<P>
   A House committee approved legislation by Rep. Frank Pallone,
D-Long Branch, to name a post office in Long Branch, N.J., after
police Sgt. Pat King, who was killed in action in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rodney Frelinghuysen, R-Harding, proposed restructuring the
New Deal-era Tennessee Valley Authority and selling most of its
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, introduced a bill last week
to require pipeline companies to offer more training to workers and
to test their pipelines for corrosion and mechanical defects.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Menendez, D-Union City, won House approval for a
measure requiring the Department of Transportation to study the
causes of crashes in New Jersey involving passenger vans.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-23-00 1345 </TRAILER>
