<DOCNO> APW20000723.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio and the littlest campaigners on the 2000 Senate trail  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEATFIELD, N.Y. (AP) - It's a gorgeous July morning in western
New York, perfect for cutting hay or milking cows. Instead, two
dozen farmers are outside a barn listening as U.S. Senate candidate
Rick Lazio speaks.
</P>
<P>
   Misspeaks, actually.
</P>
<P>
   As he's done at many stops, Lazio introduces his wife, Patricia,
and their two daughters, then scans the crowd for them.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're having the ball of their lives,'' Lazio says of Molly,
8, and Kelsey, 6. ''They got to milk a little calf, and of course
their week is made now with that experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Milk a calf? Not on any farm around here, the farmers murmur
among themselves, gathered on a field in this aptly named farm town
near Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really do feel like I'm home when I'm here,'' Lazio tells
them, unaware of the calf-gaffe. ''And I want you to know how
grateful I am for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling at home may be the easiest part of political life for
the 42-year-old, four-term congressman. During much of the first
two months of his campaign, Lazio's entire family has traveled with
him from Brightwaters to Buffalo and back.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strategy that keeps the youthful candidate from missing
the comforts of home while boosting him politically. ''Vote for my
dad, he's great,'' the little Lazios bellow over a PA aboard a
campaign bus rolling through Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   The image of the congressman and his family also offers a stark
contrast to the Clintons, whose marriage woes are well chronicled.
The Clinton campaign took a stab at countering the image in late
June when Chelsea Clinton showed up at her mother's side at a City
Hall press conference.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillary Clinton made it clear then that, unlike the Lazios,
her college-age daughter would not be a fixture on the campaign
trail. ''She's going to be coming and going as she chooses,'' she
said. ''You'll be seeing her sometimes, which will be a delight for
me, and that's all I can tell you.'' She hasn't been seen since.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, the Lazios.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lazio, who met her husband while studying to be a nurse,
even appears in the campaign's latest television commercial,
boosting her husband's stands on health care issues.
</P>
<P>
   And, while many newspapers were running stories about Clinton's
own recent bus tour, the reports were played alongside pictures of
a doting Daddy Lazio painting his daughter's fingernails or helping
them FEED MILK to a newborn calf.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a hometown guy, he's a real person,'' says Mary Donahue,
a court clerk attending a recent Lazio rally in Schenectady. ''Like
he said, he pumps gas, he goes to the grocery store like everybody
else.... He's winning me over.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Moeller, budget director for the town of Wheatfield,
says he was impressed by Lazio ''because he seems to be more down
to earth and more for the average, common person than I thought he
might be.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been busy,'' Patricia Lazio concedes during a Buffalo
Bisons double-header. It's near the end of a weeklong bus tour that
included three Fourth of July parades and visits to factories,
hospitals and village squares.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a little bit reluctant about bringing the girls, but
they've been having such a great time,'' she says. ''And it's so
nice that we've gotten to spend some time together.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey, who enjoys Irish step-dancing, and Molly, who takes
ballet lessons, have become favorites of photographers who can't
get enough of the sisters - hanging out of the ''Mainstream
Express'' bus distributing Lazio hats, T-shirts and bumper
stickers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio girls have grown up in a political atmosphere, joining
their dad during congressional campaigns on Long Island. But the
Senate race has taken them farther afield in one of the most
closely watched elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a once-in-a-lifetime experience for them,'' their mother
says as the pair run to watch the antics of the Bisons' mascot.
''Just the things they've seen that they could never otherwise see
doing something like this. And the exposure and the experience has
been really fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio has trouble remembering the last movie he's seen,
noting that he's been a little preoccupied with the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was going to say ''Saving Private Ryan,'' he says, but then
the correct answer comes to him - as a look of horror envelopes his
face.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was that last unbelievably bad movie that I had to
take the kids to'' - the recent ''Pokemon'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, it was painful,'' he says. ''The first 10 minutes ...
there was no human sound. For 10 minutes! I'd like to run into the
creator of 'Pokemon' in a dark alley, I tell you that much. I'd be
the savior of a lot of parents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
