<DOCNO> APW20000723.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Meeting To Open  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW PENNINGTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- North Korea's attendance at a regional
security forum here this week -- a major step toward breaking
decades of isolation -- will likely grab headlines, but the
meeting's hosts will also be grappling with their own issues of
cooperation and openness.
</P>
<P>
   At the Association of Southeast Asian Nations' annual round of
ministerial meetings, beginning Monday, the 10 ASEAN nations will
consider measures which could for the first time open up the
problems of each member-state to the scrutiny of the others. The
prospect is not appreciated by ASEAN's more closed societies, who
look upon it as interference in domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand, the outgoing chair of ASEAN, has called for a
revamping of the group ever since it failed to effectively respond
to Asia's 1997 economic crisis and the social upheaval that
followed. At Thailand's bidding, ASEAN ministers will consider the
idea of establishing a ministerial ''troika'' -- a three-country
diplomatic squad to address regional crises such as forest fires
that spread haze over frontiers and last year's violence in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, transnational crime, including trafficking in
drugs, arms and human beings, will be discussed at the ASEAN
Regional Forum for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures begin to breach a founding principle of ASEAN, set
up with five members 33 years ago as a Cold War bulwark against
communism: that a country's internal affairs, particularly its
politics, are its own affair.
</P>
<P>
   ASEAN now comprises liberal democracies like Thailand and the
Philippines as well as one-party regimes such as Laos, Vietnam and
Myanmar, also known as Burma. The other members are Brunei,
Cambodia, Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time has come for us to enhance our interaction to make
ASEAN relevant for the new globalized world,'' Thai Foreign
Minister Surin Pitsuwan said at a press conference last week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet efforts to broaden cooperation beyond traditional areas like
trade and investment -- for example, into cross-border concerns like
drugs and terrorism -- could run into opposition. Myanmar, for
example, is unlikely to welcome a discussion about drugs: The
military-run nation is the world's second-largest producer of
heroin and a big supplier of methamphetamine tablets to Thailand,
though it says it is doing all it can to combat the drug menace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Thai proposal to institute a troika system
modeled on the European Union's three-nation ad hoc group for
urgent issues could be shot down.
</P>
<P>
   ''Personally, I think that the troika is a good idea but don't
think it will go through easily,'' said Eric Teo, honorary
secretary of the Singapore Institute of International Affairs
Council, an independent think-tank. ''Unlike the EU, ASEAN may not
be quite ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ASEAN Regional Forum, Asia's biggest security conference, is
already attended by countries such as the United States, Japan,
South Korea and China, and this year, North Korea will participate
for the first time. The move comes just weeks after communist North
Korea and pro-Western South Korea held a historic summit, beginning
a thaw in their long-icy relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
