<HEADLINE> 'What Lies Beneath' Tops Box Office  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Michelle Pfeiffer, Harrison Ford and an
underwater ghost scared off mutants and animated pocket monsters at
the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer and Ford's supernatural thriller ''What Lies Beneath''
debuted as the weekend's top movie with $30.1 million, according to
studio estimates Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''X-men,'' the mutant superhero adventure that was last
weekend's winner, slipped to second place with $23.7 million,
pushing its total to $99.5 million in just 10 days. The movie's
three-day gross took a big drop of 56 percent from its $54.5
million opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pokemon the Movie 2000,'' the second cartoon installment based
on the pocket-monster craze, opened at No. 3 with $21.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The teen romance ''Loser,'' starring Jason Biggs and Mena Suvari
of ''American Pie,'' premiered at No. 7 with $6.1 million. Another
youth movie, the critically trashed thriller ''The In Crowd,''
debuted weakly at No. 12 with $1.5 million over the weekend,
raising its take since opening Wednesday to $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's new movies all received mixed reviews, but
audiences did not appear to mind. Overall, the top 12 movies
grossed $130 million, up 14 percent from the same weekend a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   So far this season, studio revenues have run 2 to 3 percent
ahead of last summer, when movies grossed a record $3 billion, said
Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations, which tracks
box office figures. Revenues had been lower just a few weeks ago,
before huge opening weekends for ''Scary Movie'' and ''X-men.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Definitely, summer's back in a big way,'' Dergarabedian said.
''It means audiences want to go the movies. You just have to give
them something they want to see, and studios are delivering right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Zemeckis, ''What Lies Beneath'' centers on a
wife haunted by watery visions of a missing woman with mysterious
ties to her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ''This particular movie at this particular time filled a gap,''
said Jim Tharp, head of distribution for DreamWorks, which released
''What Lies Beneath.'' ''There wasn't much out there for adults,
and especially for adult females.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences for ''What Lies Beneath'' were 61 percent women and 64
percent over 25, Tharp said.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Pokemon'' sequel took in $9.5 million less than its
predecessor grossed over its opening weekend last November.
</P>
<P>
   '''Pokemon' certainly is not as strong in the marketplace as it
was when we opened the first one,'' said Dan Fellman, head of
distribution for Warner Bros., which released both movies. ''But
it's still a strong indication there are a lot of 'Pokemon' fans
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. Final
figures are to be released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   1. ''What Lies Beneath,'' $30.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   2. ''X-men,'' $23.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   3. ''Pokemon the Movie 2000,'' $21.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   4. ''Scary Movie,'' $14.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   5. ''The Perfect Storm,'' $9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   6. ''Disney's The Kid,'' $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   7 (tie). ''Loser,'' $6.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   7 (tie). ''The Patriot,'' $6.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   9. ''Chicken Run,'' $4.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   10. ''Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' $3.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
