<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zemeckis Compares Thrillers, Comedy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Director Robert Zemeckis, best known for his
comedies, says making his first thriller had a lot in common with
directing for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Zemeckis' supernatural mystery ''What Lies Beneath'' opened
Friday. The film stars Michelle Pfeiffer and Harrison Ford as a
couple whose idyllic life is disrupted by the vengeful ghost of a
young woman.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a laughing matter, but the director of ''Forrest
Gump,'' the ''Back to the Future'' movies and ''Who Framed Roger
Rabbit?'' said setting up a scare was the same as setting up a
joke.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's a little too fast, it won't be scary. If it's a little
too slow, it won't be scary,'' Zemeckis, 48, said in Sunday's
Orange County Register.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for a good joke, the director says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Zemeckis said he felt compelled to include comic relief
to offset the jolts in his new thriller.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't seem to help myself,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 1530 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
