<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Man Wins Hemingway Contest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Carlie Coley may look like Ernest
Hemingway, but he admits he doesn't share the famous writer's
literary talents.
</P>
<P>
   Coley of Alma, Ga., won the coveted Ernest ''Papa'' Hemingway
Look-Alike Contest during the annual Hemingway Days Festival at Key
West on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old says he's written thousands of plumbing and
electrical invoices, but he says his attempts at prose are ''not
anything that anybody would want to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley, a semi-retired plumbing and electrical supply owner,
competed in the contest for four years prior to his victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried to groom myself to look as much like him as I could
and put on a little more weight, though I don't know whether that
helped or hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway lived in Key West from 1929 to 1939, where he wrote
''For Whom the Bell Tolls,'' ''To Have and Have Not'' and ''Green
Hills of Africa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
