<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Fears GOP Tax Cuts  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM C. MANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton fears that the piecemeal
approach to cutting taxes by the Republican-controlled Congress
will undermine the budget surplus rather than reduce the national
debt, top Clinton aides said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The third-ranking Republican in the House, Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, contended that Clinton is playing politics with the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, the White House's budget chief, said on ''Fox News
Sunday'' that Clinton wants to cut taxes. ''I think the president's
made clear that there is the ability to do tax cuts this year,''
Lew said. ''The question is, 'How should we cut taxes, and in what
context?'''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Republicans sent Clinton a tax-cut package that
would have cost $792 billion. Clinton vetoed it.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats contend congressional leaders decided this year to
pass basically the same package, but in pieces, item by item.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Clinton said the overall effect of the planned tax
breaks, plus higher interest because of slower payment of the debt,
would eat up the entire $2.2 trillion non-Social Security and
Medicare budget surplus projected for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Lew, White House chief of staff John Podesta and Sen. Richard
Durbin, D-Ill., repeated the same theme on Sunday's television news
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation already has passed Congress that would reduce taxes
on married couples and repeal the federal estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has promised to veto both as unaffordable.
</P>
<P>
   How much they would cost depends on who is making the estimate.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Clinton contends easing the income tax marriage
penalty would cost $250 billion over 10 years; Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., the Senate majority whip, on CNN's ''Late Edition'' put
the figure at $90 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it costs, Clinton offered last month to make the bill
law if Congress would enact a universal prescription drug program
for Medicare patients, which he said also would cost $250 billion
over 10 years. The nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office
estimated last week it actually would cost $400 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said that he would sign the marriage penalty if we gave him
a prescription drug benefit. But everybody knows that his
prescription drug benefit would never pass the House and the
Senate, and therefore it couldn't be done,'' DeLay said Sunday on
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ''So he's the one playing politics here. We're trying to do
something substantive.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay did not shut the door on compromise. Asked what GOP
leaders would do should Clinton do as he says he will and veto the
legislation, DeLay said:
</P>
<P>
   ''What's open to us is to go back and try to override his veto.
Then after that, we've got one more procedural move, called
reconciliation, in September, where we can package up some
tax-fairness issues in another package to send him.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta indicated the Clinton administration might be receptive.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president is for tax cuts,'' he on ABC's ''This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's for targeted middle-class tax cuts, and, hopefully, by
the end of this Congress, maybe we could come together and put the
partisanship aside and see if we can work something out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 1616 </TRAILER>
