<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorists to be offered personalized traffic updates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Motorists in the New York metropolitan area
may soon be offered personalized traffic reports by fax, e-mail,
phone and pager.
</P>
<P>
   Called ''Trips123,'' the $14 million project, coordinated by the
state governments and the private sector, is expected to be
available by January.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will involve three private companies, 16 transit
agencies and the transportation departments of New York, New Jersey
and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   For an undetermined fee, commuters will have access to
information from 29 counties in New York, Connecticut and northern
New Jersey, The Star-Ledger of Newark reported in Sunday's
editions.
</P>
<P>
   Government agencies said they hope the plan will cut down on
traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies such as Parsons Brinckerhoff want to make a
profit by offering consumers personalized information.
</P>
<P>
   ''People no longer want to just get their traffic information
from the radio; they want to go and get the information and do
their own travel plans,'' said Paul Carris, an engineer at the
consulting firm in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, subscribers fill out applications detailing
the routes they regularly take. That information is filed on a
computer that will alert the customer of any traffic problems along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ''So if you know you're going from Morristown to Stamford each
day, and there's any problems on the roadways or transit routes,
the system will notify you by either phone, fax, e-mail, cell
phone, or it will page you en route,'' Carris said. ''However,
whenever you want to get the information, it will get to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic and construction information will be available for free
on a Web site. There will also be a Web program to help travelers
coordinate trips involving various forms of transit.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic information will be available by phone, but not on a
toll-free line.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the traffic information will come from the system of
sensors, satellites and electronic warning signs wired into the
area's network of highways, bridges and tunnels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
