<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coverdell Successor Unknown  </HEADLINE>
By DICK PETTYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Speculation reigned Sunday as Georgia political
leaders waited for Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes to name a successor
to Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever Barnes picks would have an edge in the Nov. 7
nonpartisan special election to fill the remaining four years in
Coverdell's term.
</P>
<P>
   That draws attention both inside and outside Georgia because a
Democratic victory would tip the balance of power closer toward
even in the U.S. Senate, where Republicans now hold a 54-45
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Former Democratic Gov. Zell Miller was said to be Barnes' most
likely pick following Coverdell's death last week at the age of 61.
</P>
<P>
   However, Miller, who has been teaching at Georgia universities,
was believed to be weighing whether he wanted to re-enter public
life at age 68.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather not talk about it right now,'' Miller said Sunday
from his home in the northeast Georgia mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Miller left the governorship in 1999 after eight years in which
his popularity soared, largely because of a lottery-funded program
that provides college scholarships to students with ''B'' averages.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever Barnes names, GOP leaders were looking to their party's
members of Georgia's congressional delegation to ensure that a
Republican wins in November.
</P>
<P>
   One name mentioned prominently was Rep. Johnny Isakson, although
other GOP congressmen also were said to be interested.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson, elected last year to the seat formerly held by House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, said Sunday that the eight Republican
congressmen had talked about uniting behind a candidate in November
and planned to meet again this week.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate would have to earn 50 percent of the vote in
November's nonpartisan election or the two candidates with the most
votes would go to a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford to get two, three or four Republicans in the
race against one well-funded Democrat,'' said Chuck Clay, the state
Republican Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican congressmen mentioned included Bob Barr, John
Linder and Jack Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University political science professor Merle Black said
each of those would be at a disadvantage, either because they were
not well-known outside their districts or were too conservative for
an election in which voters from both parties could participate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
