<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Might Ban Relief Flights  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) -- Sudan's president has threatened to bar
foreign relief planes from delivering humanitarian aid to the
war-torn south, raising concern Sunday among U.N. food workers.
</P>
<P>
   President Omar el-Bashir accused Operation Lifeline Sudan, a
relief effort involving U.N. and voluntary agencies, of helping
rebels battling government troops in the south. He said his
government will not allow planes taking off from outside the
country to bring aid to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not allow OLS ... to be used for the provision of
assistance to the rebels,'' el-Bashir said late Saturday in a
ceremony aimed at rallying support for the government war effort in
southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Lifeline Sudan uses the northern Kenya town of Lokichokio as its
base.
</P>
<P>
   El-Bashir has suspended OLS operations several times in the
past, calling it a cover for the arms smuggling to the Sudan
People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Makena Walker, a spokeswoman for the U.N. World Food Program in
Khartoum, said Sunday her organization hasn't been officially
notified of el-Bashir's announcement and that flights were going as
normal.
</P>
<P>
   But if implemented, the president's decision would create ''a
worrisome'' situation in the south, she said. Flooding, fighting
and drought have left 1.7 million Sudanese in need of food
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The SPLA has led a rebellion for autonomy in the largely
Christian and animist south from the predominantly Muslim and
Arabized north since 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
