<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: FBI looking at Paterson mayor's world travels  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PATERSON, N.J. (AP) - The FBI has begun looking at the world
travels of Mayor Marty Barnes, in an effort to search for possible
links between contractors who paid for the trips and publicly
funded business they received, according to a published report.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who has made international travel a hallmark of his
three years in office, has been to Switzerland, the Dominican
Republic, Russia's Caucasus Mountains and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has said some of the travels were an attempt to set up an
international trade zone in the economically depressed city and
help local businesses make contact with their counterparts abroad;
he said others were to review companies doing business with the
city.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sunday's editions of The Record of Hackensack, the
FBI investigation is focusing in particular on trips to Brazil and
Switzerland because they were funded by contractors who either
received millions of dollars in publicly funded business or were
seeking such business.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is the company that Barnes recommends to the council the best
company, or is he recommending them because they have given him
gifts?'' Councilman Thomas C. Rooney Jr. told the newspaper. ''I
can't answer that question. That is the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has requested the mayor's appointment diaries, message
books, phone bills, travel records and records of gifts he
received, among other documents.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the FBI has also interviewed Barnes at his home
and seized records relating to three sewage system contractors who
do business with the city. All three contractors paid for portions
of Barnes' trips abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he took those trips - one to Brazil and one to
Switzerland - in order to review the systems before the city spent
millions of dollars on them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The solution to the city's sewer problems will cost us in
excess of $34 million and the technology does not exist in the
United States,'' Barnes wrote in a March report to the city
council. ''It was prudent for us to review an existing system
before recommending a solution worth millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rooney and others say they're worried that the companies may
have had a better shot at the contracts after paying for the trips.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Cincinnati used city money on similar trips last
year to Austria and Switzerland last year to look at sewer systems.
One official, who asked not to be named, said his boss wouldn't
have allowed a contractor to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ''For us, it would have been a conflict of interest to have one
of the companies pay for the trip,'' he told the newspaper. ''You
don't want to feel obligated to use the company that you visited.
You're there for an independent view of their product. You want to
stay as independent as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   After repeated requests, Barnes in March gave the council a
report on the trips that did not include details about who paid. He
said that information was nobody's business since public money was
not used to finance the trips.
</P>
<P>
   ''It involves public officials, public money,'' Rooney said.
''The public is entitled to know this. The secrecy of this is
terrible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-23-00 1625 </TRAILER>
