<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Clears Road in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- An offensive by U.N. peacekeepers
has pushed a breakaway military faction from a strategic road
leading into Sierra Leone's capital, officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's U.N. mission, code-named Operation Thunderbolt, was
the latest move by the world body to flex the muscles of a
peacekeeping force that had been embarrassed by kidnappings and
military defeats since May.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the operation were scanty, but at least one
peacekeeper was wounded in clashes. U.N. spokeswoman Hirut Befecadu
said it ''successfully'' cleared a small renegade faction of
nominally pro-government fighters known as the West Side Boys away
from a road connecting Freetown and the international airport in
Lungi.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. military officer speaking on condition of anonymity said
the operation involved heavily armed U.N. ground troops and
helicopter gunships. An unknown number of renegades were killed,
the officer said.
</P>
<P>
   Befecadu could not confirm the enemy casualties but said one
Guinean U.N. peacekeeper was critically injured by retreating
renegade fighters. U.N. troops from Nigeria and other nations are
patrolling the road to maintain security, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The operation was very intense to clear the road,'' Befecadu
said. ''Nobody is running around (there) anymore with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last month, the West Side Boys were part of a fragile
pro-government alliance fighting Sierra Leone's feared rebel
Revolutionary United Front rebels. But the faction has fallen out
with the government after allegedly attacking other pro-government
fighters and carrying out a spree of carjackings, robberies and
rapes.
</P>
<P>
   The 13,000-strong U.N. force in Sierra Leone has recently begun
using force to restore its credibility in the wake of the
kidnapping of hundreds of its peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July, U.N. troops backed by British and Indian attack
helicopters launched a military rescue of more than 200
peacekeepers who had been surrounded by rebels since early May. One
Indian U.N. peacekeeper was killed and seven injured in that
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Also this weekend, a contingent of 230 combat-experienced troops
from Britain's Royal Irish Regiment arrived in Sierra Leone to
train about 1,000 new Sierra Leonean recruits, British army
spokesman Capt. Fergus Smith said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest arrivals replace a contingent that just completed
training another group of 986 Sierra Leonean troops. Britain has
also donated arms and military equipment to help Sierra Leone's
elected government.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone military officials said the new recruits would soon
be deployed to frontline positions to fight the RUF rebels, who
reignited the country's eight-year civil war in May.
</P>
<P>
   Since the civil war began in 1991, the rebels have
systematically killed and maimed tens of thousands of people in a
bid to gain control of the government and the country's lucrative
diamond-mining region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
