<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Settlers Will Refuse To Leave  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA BLIJDENSTEIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PSAGOT, West Bank (AP) -- Peace deal or no peace deal, Jewish
settlers in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip said Sunday that they
will refuse to leave their homes no matter what is decided at the
Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak, conferring at the summit with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, has said that up to one-quarter,
or 50,000, of the 200,000 settlers may be left outside the umbrella
of Israeli sovereignty as part of an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal would give the Palestinians the state they seek, but
Jewish settlers consider the land their biblical birthright.
</P>
<P>
   Settler leader Zeev Hever said most of the settlers will stay
put even if an agreement stipulates that they have to evacuate
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no power in the world that can uproot tens of
thousands of Jews,'' Hever said at a meeting in this well-to-do
bedroom community that juts into the crowded,
Palestinian-controlled town of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, the settlers said they were confident
the army would never obey government orders to abandon them or
evacuate them. The army has repeatedly said it would carry out the
mandate of any peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, about a dozen members of Betar, a hard-line youth
group, brought a herd of sheep to the prime minister's residence
Sunday. ''We will not go like sheep to the slaughter,'' chanted the
group as they held onto the sheep with leashes.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers said they are preparing for the worst, including
the possibility of violent confrontations with local Palestinians.
They have asked the government for more bulletproof vests, and some
settlements have stocked up on battle gear including night-vision
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Palestinians will resort to violence, we have
self-defense units, we are not untrained,'' said Yisrael Medad.
''We know the Palestinians want war, we have to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlers got some succor from Barak's foreign minister,
David Levy, when he visited their protest tent. Levy, who has a
history of bolting Cabinets during government crises, refused to
tell reporters whether or not he was contemplating resigning.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was never talk about uprooting settlements'' before
Barak left, Levy said. ''There is no such thing like a peace at any
price, that's what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Further defections would seriously weaken Barak, who is already
governing with a minority coalition. Three parties defected as soon
as he announced his intention to attend the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the summit succeeds or fails, Israeli security officials
are preparing for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Environment Minister Dalia Itzik said that at Sunday's Cabinet
meeting, the head of the Shin Bet, Israel's internal security
service, said hard-line extremists had threatened the lives of both
Barak and Arafat. The intelligence chief added that to date there
had been no attempts to carry out those threats, Itzik said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak spokesmen said the issue of Jerusalem -- a seemingly
intractable problem that nearly derailed the summit last week -- was
central to coming to an agreement. Barak has pledged to keep the
holy city united, although the Palestinians say they will only sign
an agreement that gives them full sovereignty of the city's eastern
sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jerusalem is the heart of the Jewish people, and it could well
be the heart of this agreement,'' Barak spokesman Gadi Baltiansky
told Israel television. He said the summit's success could hinge on
coming to an agreement on the bitterly disputed city.
</P>
<P>
   Another spokesman, Yoni Koren, told Israel radio that the 24
hours after President Clinton returned to the summit on Sunday were
going to be ''critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak associates have said Israel might accept a U.S. bridging
proposal that would extend limited Palestinian sovereignty to parts
of east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Yossi Beilin, an architect of the breakthrough
peace accords that led to the marathon summit outside Washington,
led a tour Sunday through traditionally Arab east Jerusalem,
captured by Israel during the 1967 Mideast war. During the tour,
Beilin said it was time for Israel to unburden itself of some of
the Palestinian neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is most important is to see the lack of importance and
meaning of these villages for Israel,'' he said. ''They fall
outside the core of our Jerusalem and we have to differentiate
between our Jerusalem and the Jerusalem that is not ours and never
was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
