<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Chief Welcomes G-8 Trade Round  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- The head of the World Trade Organization on Sunday
welcomed the call by leaders of the Group of Eight industrial
countries for a new round of global trade talks, but said support
from developing countries would be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a splendid thing if we could launch a round this
year,'' said WTO Director-General Mike Moore in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The support expressed by G-8 leaders at the summit in Nago,
Okinawa, is an important first step, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the WTO makes all of its important decisions by consensus
and while agreement on a package of negotiations from the Group of
Eight is welcome, there can be no launch of talks without support
from the world's developing countries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said a new round of global trade talks would offer the
best way to ensure balanced negotiations capable of encompassing
the interests and concerns of all the WTO's more than 130 members --
and not just its richest members.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only through a round can you get the trade-offs that benefit
the smallest and most vulnerable societies,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings last year in Seattle to prepare for a new round of
global trade talks collapsed amid acrimony between developing and
developed nations after violent demonstrations against the ill
effects of globalization erupted in the streets.
--------------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.wto.org/english/thewto--e/whatis--e/tif--e/fact4--e.htm
</P>
<P>
   http://www.g8kyushu-okinawa.go.jp/
</P>
</TEXT>
