<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Disease Plan Will Cost $25B  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- A campaign against killer diseases announced
Sunday by leaders of the Group of Eight industrial countries will
cost at least $25 billion over the next five years, a U.N. health
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization welcomed the commitment by leaders
of the G-8 meeting in Nago, Okinawa, to work to slash the number of
deaths worldwide from three of the planet's most deadly killers:
AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria.
</P>
<P>
   These three diseases account for nearly 5 million deaths a year,
the agency said in a statement Sunday. That's half of all
fatalities worldwide from infectious diseases -- the leading cause
of death in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''These deaths occur primarily among the poorest people because
they do not have access to the drugs and commodities necessary for
prevention and cure,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency warned that fighting the diseases will be
expensive and will require world governments to coordinate their
efforts with the United Nations and private companies and
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line: additional investment of $5 billion a year
for at least the next five years,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   In the final communique of their summit, the leaders of the G-8
vowed over the next 10 years to cut by a quarter the number of
young people worldwide infected with HIV and to halve the number of
deaths from tuberculosis. It also promised to combat diseases
associated with malaria.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization said fighting HIV would be the
costliest part of the effort, consuming 60 percent of funds. Most
of that should be spent on HIV prevention, including mother to
child transmission, and care for people already infected with the
AIDS virus, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money should be split evenly for the campaigns
against malaria and TB, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
