<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Archbishop Dyba Dies at 70  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Archbishop Johannes Dyba, considered one of
Germany's most conservative clergymen for his outspoken views
against abortion and domestic partnerships, has died. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   He died in his sleep Saturday night of heart failure, officials
in his office said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Dyba, who was archbishop of the Fulda diocese in central Germany
and the Roman Catholic bishop for the military, polarized Germans
and even caused controversy within the church with his often
pointed comments on questions of morality.
</P>
<P>
   His most harsh criticism was focused against abortion, which he
called a ''children's Holocaust.'' In recent weeks, he also aimed
his barbs at talk within the government of giving legal rights to
gay couples, calling such moves ''a further fatal step in the
degeneration.''
</P>
<P>
   Those remarks drew strong criticism from many politicians as
well as lawsuits against him filed by homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Born Sept. 15, 1929 in Berlin, Dyba as a child wanted to be a
boxer, pilot or missionary. He studied law, including at Duke
University in North Carolina, before deciding to enter the
priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   He was ordained in 1959 in Cologne and after a short time
serving in churches went to study in Rome. He served the Vatican in
diplomatic posts in Buenos Aires, Argentina; The Hague,
Netherlands; Kinshasa, Congo, and Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1983, he was named the head of the Fulda diocese,
and in 1990 also became the Catholic military bishop, visiting
German troops on missions in Yugoslavia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the last Monday he had said he would give up his
position as military bishop as soon as a successor was named.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
