<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City expands spraying after two more dead birds are found  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -The discovery of two more dead birds infected
with West Nile virus prompted the city on Sunday to expand its
battle against disease-carrying mosquitoes into new areas of Queens
and Brooklyn, while going ahead with further efforts in Staten
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said there still have been no reports of
humans afflicted with the sometimes deadly ailment. Seven elderly
people died and more than 60 were made ill by an outbreak of the
imported virus a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''So far it's not as bad as last year,'' Giuliani said. ''First
of all, it hasn't infected a mosquito as far as we know, we haven't
found a mosquito, and even that's one step before you get to what
happened last year, which was a significant number of human beings
contracting the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and City Health Commissioner Dr. Neal Cohen said the
new assault on the disease would include spraying of a short-lived
insecticide by trucks and ''larvacide'' pellets or granules dropped
into selected pools, catch basins and other standing-water sites
where mosquitoes can breed.
</P>
<P>
   ''People should not be alarmed, should not be concerned. These
are all things that we assumed we would have to do,'' Giuliani
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing unusual is happening. The plan that we had from the
very beginning - if we were to find birds, or even if we were to
find mosquitoes - infected with the virus, we would then spray. So
far we've proceeded to do that, and hopefully it will keep this
under control.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials said spraying by trucks would begin on Tuesday
night in two two-square mile sections of Queens, including Richmond
Hill and Woodhaven, plus Cypress Hills and other parts of Brooklyn.
The seven-hour spraying will end at 5 a.m. and the insecticide,
Anvil, will deterioriate after a few hours in sunlight, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Those areas were targeted after the two dead birds tested
positiive by the state health department. One was a crow, found in
Richmond Hill July 3. The other, found in Woodhaven July 13, was a
merlin, a small falcon common in Newfoundland and eastern Canada
but rare in this area.
</P>
<P>
   The tests raised to seven the number of dead birds recently
found to be infected, among more than 220 examined for the disease,
Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Previously planned spraying will proceed on Monday night in
another section Queens and all of Staten Island not previously
treated, Giuliani said. He said the National Parks Service has
approved the program in the Gateway National Recreation Area.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters may be used to deliver the larvacide to water
sources in Staten Island that are not otherwise easily reached. The
target sites have not yet been selected, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ''bacterial larvacide'' is designed to kill the
mosquitoes where they breed but is non-toxic to fish and other
life. ''It can be very safely applied in ponds, lakes, streams and
other wetlands and environmentally sensitive areas without
concern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The areas to be sprayed on Tuesday include all or part of the
Queens neighborhoods of Rego park, Forest Hills, Middle Village,
Glendale, Lindenwood, Kew Gardens, Ozone Park, South Ozone Park,
Woodhaven and Richmomd Hill, and Brooklyn sections of East New
York, Highland Park, Cypress Hills and City Line.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said it made sense to concentrate efforts on areas where
dead birds are found because once infected, ''they become sedentary
and very vulnerable'' to being bitten by other mosquitoes that then
become carriers, spreading the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester County plans to begin spraying after a number of
dead birds were found recently. Connecticut also will start
spraying in communities where a number of dead mosquitoes carrying
the virus were found recently. The state has been testing dead
birds, but so far has not found the virus in them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
