<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio's spokesman: 'I will believe Clinton's denial'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The chief campaign strategist for Rep. Rick
Lazio said Sunday that he believes Hillary Rodham Clinton's
assertion that she did not use an anti-Semitic obscenity, but he
added that she has a ''credibility problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Murphy, who works for the Republican Senate candidate, was
asked on CNN's ''Late Edition'' if he believes she used the
offensive term.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy answered: ''I have no way to know. I will believe her
denial, but I will say, and I think most New Yorkers will say,
there's an unease about trustworthiness of Mrs. Clinton, because
there's such a history of spin taken to the ultimate with the
Clintons, that she has a credibility problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Lazio expressed doubts about her denial, saying: ''I
don't know who to believe. I don't think New Yorkers know who to
believe. And therein lies a good deal of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was accused of using the term ''Jew b------'' in an
argument with Paul Fray in 1974, after Bill Clinton lost a
congressional campaign in Arkansas. Fray had worked on the campaign
and later lost his license to practice law because he accepted a
bribe to change a guilty verdict in a court docket.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation surfaced in a new book, ''State of a Union,'' by
Jerry Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady vehemently denied the allegation in an emotional
press conference last week at her Chappaqua home and released a
letter Fray had sent to her in 1997 begging forgiveness for lies he
told about her.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Lazio had tried to ''promote'' the accusation by
publicly doubting Clinton's denial, Murphy said: ''Of course not.
What happened was, it's a New York Senate campaign, which means
it's highly entertaining and there's a new, explosive, crazy issue
every week. And Mrs. Clinton's had a very bad week because of these
allegations. What Rick said after days of questioning, and I think
what he said before, the problem is who knows who to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was also asked if he believes the first lady is
anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, I don't,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
