<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Crunch Salary Numbers  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- If Washington Redskins running back Stephen
Davis catches just one touchdown pass this season, he will earn a
bonus of about $1.5 million -- and it won't count against the salary
cap.
</P>
<P>
   How come? That particular achievement, using the NFL's legalese,
is ''not likely to be earned.''
</P>
<P>
   How can that be? Because it just so happens that Davis, even
though he led the NFC and set a franchise record with 1,405 yards
rushing, didn't catch a single touchdown pass last year. He did
have two TD receptions in 1998, but all that matters when figuring
''not likely'' incentives is whether a player improves in a
particular stat from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   That's one way to get around the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Such financial wheelings and dealings were flying fast and
furious Saturday when the Redskins signed their last two holdouts,
Davis and No. 2 overall draft pick LaVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm eager to understand all these things on my own,''
Arrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Have a seat, LaVar. It could take a while.
</P>
<P>
   The record will show that Davis signed a one-year, $3.532
million contract with a $1 million signing bonus, and that
Arrington's deal covers six years for a shade under $36 million
with a $10.75 million signing bonus and a voidable seventh year.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the numbers that count, in one way or other, against
the salary cap. Reality is far different. For instance, if
Arrington is on the field for just 35 percent of the defensive
plays this season -- a sure thing unless he gets hurt -- a series of
''escalators'' kick in that would earn him at least another $4
million -- cap-free.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington held out for six days because he wanted more money
than No. 1 overall pick Courtney Brown got from Cleveland. Such a
deal would have upset the natural order of the NFL universe, and
the Redskins weren't about to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, agents Kevin and Carl Poston -- brothers whom
Arrington called his ''two-headed dragon'' -- said the six-year deal
matches Brown's dollar-for-dollar for the first three years and is
slightly less than Brown's for the last three.
</P>
<P>
   But here comes the spin. Kevin Poston said that if Arrington
meets every possible incentive in the contract, he would earn more
than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''His overall package is more than Courtney's,'' Poston said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington's holdout was standard fare these days. Davis'
negotiations, however, were especially bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had never complained about being a backup. He even
volunteered to play out of position at fullback for a season after
a teammate was injured, and he literally took one for the team when
he got sucker-punched by receiver Michael Westbrook and didn't
raise a fuss about it.
</P>
<P>
   After his great year in 1999, Davis felt it was his turn to get
one of those huge contracts signed by so many of his peers. When
the Redskins made a first offer that would have paid him only $1.5
million in salary and bonus the first year, Davis was so insulted
he walked out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stephen Davis hasn't been the same since,'' his agent, Steve
Weinberg, said.
</P>
<P>
   Countering what he considered to be a joke offer with his own
joke, Weinberg suggested a $100 million contract with a $14 million
signing bonus. Acrimony was high. The Redskins designated Davis
their franchise player to keep him from becoming a free agent, and
the two sides went months without talking.
</P>
<P>
   It took a girl about to turn 16 to get things going. On
Thursday, when the full camp started, Weinberg's daughter,
Michelle, said: ''Dad, this is absurd.'' She typed a fax and, with
some minor editing from Dad, it was sent to the Redskins. Contact
was re-established.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, Davis had agreed to a one-year contract
that at least gets him in camp while Weinberg and the Redskins work
on a long-term deal. Weinberg thinks it's a landmark deal that
franchise players will demand in future years: It has a no-trade
clause, a likely-but-''not-likely'' incentive, and -- in case they
can't work out a long-term deal -- it states that the Redskins can't
put the franchise tag on Davis again next year if he meets some
routine standards, such as 800 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously silent on the Redskins' big day were the Redskins
themselves. Director of player personnel Vinny Cerrato refused to
comment and didn't even present either of his signees at their
press conferences, leaving the agents to win the spin doctor game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Cerrato's just worn out from all that cap maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Arrington took part in his first practice Sunday and was
worked hard by linebackers coach Foge Fazio. ''He did fair,'' Fazio
said. ''He's out of shape, and he needs a lot of work.'' ...
Arrington and the other first- and second-stringers then moved to
the sideline while the third and fourth units took part in an
intrasquad scrimmage. Among the standouts: QB Todd Husak (22-yard
TD pass to Derrius Thompson) and RB Chad Dukes (10-yard TD run).
... The Redskins signed RB Gerard Arnold and waived WR Ethan Howell
and LB Andre Reed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 1848 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000723.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> J.R. Redmond Signs With Patriots  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Third-round pick J.R. Redmond has signed a
four-year contract with the New England Patriots, more than a week
after the running back was scheduled to report to training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was worth a reported $1.681 million. His signing bonus,
which was reduced during the holdout, was $300,000, team spokesman
Stacey James said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, out of Arizona State, received the highest average
salary of any third-round choice. But his signing bonus was about
$200,000 less than the amount slotted for that spot.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond isn't ready to practice after undergoing surgery last
month to repair an inflamed tendon in his groin. He will compete
with second-year pro Kevin Faulk and Raymont Harris, formerly of
the Chicago Bears and Green Bay Packers, for the vacant running
back job. Terry Allen, last year's starter, wasn't re-signed after
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also signed free agent linebacker Rob Holmberg, a
six-year NFL veteran who played last season with the Minnesota
Vikings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 1851 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000723.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbus man claims he's sailor in famous V-J Day photo  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Aug. 15, 1945, sailor Ernie Dubay was working as a guard at
St. Albans Naval Hospital in Queens, N.Y., when he heard on the
radio that Japan had surrendered and the war was over.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as his shift ended, he hopped on the subway to Times
Square, where he knew there'd be a party going on. He came up from
the subway, saw a nurse in white, bent her over and kissed her.
</P>
<P>
   A photographer happened to be there and snapped the pair
kissing. That photographer happened to be Alfred Eisenstaedt, who
worked for Life magazine, Dubay said. And that picture happened to
become the symbol of the joy and relief the nation felt on V-J Day
and one of the most famous photos ever taken.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstaedt didn't identify his subjects. In the 55 years since
it was taken, about two dozen men have claimed they're the sailor.
But Dubay, a retired school principal who lives in Columbus, N.J.,
insists he's the one.
</P>
<P>
   Why did he wait 55 years?
</P>
<P>
   Because he was more interested in peace at home than his place
in photographic history.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never told my wife because we were going steady at the time,
and I should have been home kissing her instead of being in Times
Square kissing that girl,'' he said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   His wife wouldn't have understood, he said, and he couldn't get
up the nerve to tell her. The longer he waited, the harder it got.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know how you look down from a high diving board and it
looks like it's 10 feet, and you look again and it looks like 15?''
Dubay said. ''That's how it was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 52 years they were married, Dubay never told his wife his
secret. She died in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He waited until now to go public because he ran for office in
Columbus last year and he didn't want his neighbors to think his
claim was a campaign stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Dubay doesn't want fame or fortune, he just wants to set the
record straight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't need the notoriety, but I saw these fellows claimed
they were the one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Years after the photo was taken, Life magazine identified the
nurse as Edith Shain, of Santa Monica, Calif. She has said the
sailor was Carl Muscarello, a retired New York detective who worked
on a submarine tender during the war.
</P>
<P>
   But Dubay says that isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the man in the picture,'' the 75-year-old said. ''I've got
all the features, believe me, and I know it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   He can still see the moment in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can picture her walking down, me grabbing her, me kissing
her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't a passionate kiss. It was just a celebration kiss,''
he said. ''That's all it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The photo only shows the side of the sailor's face and his right
hand as he holds the nurse around her waist. But Dubay is hoping an
expert in photo enhancement could show the similarities to him
today.
</P>
<P>
   ''Noses don't change, chins don't change, ears don't change,
hands don't change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Romer, who teaches the history and conservation of
photography at the George Eastman House, a museum of photography in
Rochester, N.Y., said it would be possible to analyze the sailor's
features, but it would not provide a definitive answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are certain characteristics of everybody that are
distinct to them, but those characteristics can not only change
over time but they aren't always accurately rendered in a photo,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One can look at this man's ears, hands and chin and you may be
able to make a complete analysis against the information in the
picture,'' Romer said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, that won't necessarily prove that it's Dubay.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may make the case clearer that it might not be him, it will
never absolutely determine that it is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said the mystery might just be better left unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a story about human nature and human drama, that there
is more than one claimant to that. Was there more than one sailor
kissing a girl in Times Square that day? Sure. There was more than
one sailor, more than one nurse, more than one kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Dubay agreed to that much.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody was kissing everybody,'' he said. ''You know how
sailors are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
