<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hall-Of-Fame Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Carlton Fisk isn't done collecting
honors.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox will retire their former catcher's No. 27 before
their Sept. 4 game against the Seattle Mariners, general manager
Dan Duquette said Sunday before the Hall of Fame induction
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk played parts of 11 seasons with Boston before playing his
last 13 years with the Chicago White Sox. Chicago has already
retired the No. 72 he wore there.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Red Sox have said they will only retire a
number for a player who is in the Hall, spent more than 10 years
with the team and finished his career with Boston. Fisk consults
with the Red Sox front office, and Duquette said that's good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk's number will be mounted onto Fenway's right-field roof
facade along with Ted Williams' No. 9, Carl Yastrzemski's No. 8,
Bobby Doerr's No. 4, Joe Cronin's No. 1 and the No. 42 all teams
have retired in honor of Jackie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox rules require a player to finish his career with the
team, but the team overlooked that technicality in Fisk's case.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE GOOD OLD DAYS: It looks like Barry Larkin is staying with
the Cincinnati Reds for now. But Sparky Anderson said this weekend
that if free agency was as prevalent in the 1970s as it is today,
they wouldn't have been able to keep the Big Red Machine together.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, it couldn't stay together,'' Anderson said. ''There's four
or five guys there who would have to be divvied up a fifth (of the
team) apiece. And I think they'd be arguing because they'd own the
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Anderson said he's partially responsible for breaking
up the team, giving his OK to the trade that sent Perez to Montreal
after the 1976 season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tony Perez should have never left Cincinnati,'' Anderson said.
''When he left, I started to realize, 'Something's missing.'
</P>
<P>
   ''They could have sent me to the Bahamas and kept Perez and they
could have won it again.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   WAIT 'TIL NEXT YEAR: Among those eligible for the first time
next year are: Steve Bedrosian, Ron Darling, Kirk Gibson, John
Kruk, Candy Maldonado, Don Mattingly, Kirby Puckett, Dave Righetti,
Dave Stewart, Andy Van Slyke, Lou Whitaker and Dave Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LONGEVITY: Inductees are supposed to take 15 minutes for their
acceptance speech. Carlton Fisk took more like 45.
</P>
<P>
   The catching great thanked everyone from his high school
baseball coach and army reserve officers to the clubhouse manager
in Chicago, growing emotional at times.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk made the Hall by lasting longer than any catcher in
history, playing in a record 2,229 games. His defining moment was a
game-winning homer in the Game 6 of the World Series -- in the 12th
inning.
</P>
<P>
   And, when he was playing, he was known for long, slow trips to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS: Longtime Cleveland baseball writer Hal Lebovitz
was awarded the J.G. Taylor Spink Award for excellence in baseball
reporting. ... A record 45 previously inducted Hall of Famers
returned for the ceremony. Catfish Hunter, Pee Wee Reese and Bob
Lemon have died since last year's induction. ... The ceremony
opened with a recitation of ''Casey at the Bat,'' by Worcester,
Mass., native Ernest Thayer. ... Dennis DeYoung, the lead singer
from the group Styx and a White Sox fan, sang the national anthem.
... Bob Sheppard presented the Hall with the microphone he has used
for parts of the last 50 years as the New York Yankees announcer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
