<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, July 23, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Returns to Camp David
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- Hurrying back from an abbreviated trip to Asia,
President Clinton was rejoining troubled Middle East talks at Camp David today
even as American mediators spoke of the possibility of failure. ''We might reach
a deal; we might not,'' a summit spokesman said. On a 13th day of talks -- the
same period required to strike a deal at the landmark 1978 Camp David summit --
neither Israel nor the Palestinians signaled any change in position on the prime
point of dispute: Jerusalem. Both sides claim the ancient city as their capital.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Settlers Will Refuse To Leave
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PSAGOT, West Bank (AP) -- Peace deal or no peace deal, Jewish settlers in the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip said Sunday that they will refuse to leave their
homes no matter what is decided at the Camp David summit. Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, conferring at the summit with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, has said
that up to one-quarter, or 50,000, of the 200,000 settlers may be left outside
the umbrella of Israeli sovereignty as part of an agreement. Such a deal would
give the Palestinians the state they seek, but Jewish settlers consider the land
their biblical birthright.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Children Released From Hostage Standoff
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A murder suspect holding five hostages in a suburban
home released two of the four children Sunday as police tried to end the two-day
standoff. Both children, an 8-year-old boy and a girl under 1, were in good
health, although the boy was hungry and thirsty, Orange County Sheriff Kevin
Beary said.Beary said the suspect, Jamie Dean Petron, 41, had asked police to
see the children reunited with their parents on live television after releasing
them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cheney Said Sanguine on VP Chances
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush's top vice presidential candidate, former
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, has told associates there is a good chance he
will get the job, officials said today as the Republican governor from Texas
prepared to announce his pick. Cheney, former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri and
perhaps others are on Bush's short list, according to highly placed GOP
officials. In seclusion at his Texas ranch, Bush tentatively planned to
introduce his running mate Tuesday. Even his closest advisers said they did not
know if he had made up his mind today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lazio Aide Believes Clinton Denial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The chief campaign strategist for Rep. Rick Lazio said today
he believes Hillary Rodham Clinton's assertion that she did not use an
anti-Semitic slur, but he added that she has a ''credibility problem.'' Mike
Murphy, who works for the Republican Senate candidate, was asked on CNN if he
believes she used the offensive term. Murphy answered: ''I have no way to know.
I will believe her denial, but I will say, and I think most New Yorkers will
say, there's an unease about trustworthiness of Mrs. Clinton, because there's
such a history of spin taken to the ultimate with the Clintons, that she has a
credibility problem.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iran To Sign Big Oil, Gas Contract
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran this week will sign a $4.3 billion contract to
develop a massive gas field in the Persian Gulf, the official daily newspaper,
Iran, reported Sunday. The field's full reserves amount to about 6 percent of
the world's total gas reserves, according to the newspaper. It quoted what it
called informed sources as saying the contract, the biggest deal of its kind, to
develop the South Pars gas field would be signed Thursday with Italy's ENI and
Petro-Pars of Iran.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tiger Woods Completes Career Grand Slam
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- Tiger Woods stepped into history today, winning
the British open with a 19-under 269, the lowest score in relation to par ever
at a major championship. It was a fitting way for Woods to win at the home of
golf, making him the youngest player ever to complete the career Grand Slam.
Woods becomes only the fifth player to win all four majors, the first since Jack
Nicklaus won the 1966 British Open.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds Dominate BB Hall Inductions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- The Big Red Machine's presence in Cooperstown got a
lot bigger on today when Tony Perez and Sparky Anderson were inducted into the
Baseball Hall of Fame alongside World Series nemesis Carlton Fisk. ''There seem
to be a lot of guys up here that I played against in '75,'' said Fisk, who hit a
game-winning homer in the 12th inning of Game 6 only to see Perez homer in Game
7 to deliver the Series to the Reds. Perez and Anderson join Cincinnati
teammates Joe Morgan and Johnny Bench in the Hall. All-time hit king Pete Rose
is ineligible, having been banned from baseball for gambling
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
