<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tel Aviv Proposes Light Rail System  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel announced plans Sunday for a light rail
system for Tel Aviv that would link the increasingly congested
city's northern and southern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The subway's first line would link the town of Petach Tikva,
north of Tel Aviv, with Bat Yam in the south, the Finance Ministry
and the Tel Aviv municipality said in announcing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the first line would be above ground, but 2&AMP;frac12; miles would
run under central Tel Aviv, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials did not announce costs or a timetable for the
planned light rail system.
</P>
<P>
   Tel Aviv and its suburbs constitute a metropolis that encompass
over a million people along Israel's Mediterranean coast. In recent
years, traffic jams have increased.
</P>
<P>
   Tel Aviv has contemplated launching a subway at least since the
1991 Gulf War, when Iraq aimed Scud missiles at the city. City
authorities noted that, in other cities, subways had proven the
most effective bomb shelters during bombing attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 1927 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000723.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Backs FDA Check of Cholestin  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration should be allowed
to regulate a dietary supplement made from a substance that is
chemically identical to the active ingredient in a drug that lowers
cholesterol, an appeals court has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Friday that a
federal court in Utah erred when it said the FDA could not regulate
the dietary supplement Cholestin.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA had banned imports of red yeast powder containing
mevinolin, which is used to make Cholestin. Because mevinolin is
identical to a synthetic drug -- sold as Mevacor and prescribed to
lower cholesterol -- the agency regarded the powder as an unapproved
drug.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Court Judge Dale Kimball last year ruled that
FDA's ban was illegal under a 1994 federal law because Cholestin
clearly fit the definition of ''dietary supplement'' and could not
be regulated by the agency as a drug.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball said the law allows FDA to regulate finished products --
but not their ingredients -- as drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court disagreed, saying the intent of the law was
ambiguous and that to interpret it as applying only to finished
drug products ''would be to restrict its scope so as to render it a
meaningless limitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision sends the case back to district court for decisions
on unresolved arguments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 1928 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000723.0083 </DOCNO>
