<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grant Cottage a link to nation's past  </HEADLINE>
By RIK STEVENS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILTON, N.Y. (AP) - At 8:08 Sunday morning, the men of the Sons
of Union Veterans Camp 154 paused outside their tents and gazed
northwest toward the top of Mt. McGregor.
</P>
<P>
   It was 115 years ago to the minute that President Ulysses S.
Grant died in a cottage atop the mountain, finally succumbing to
the throat cancer he raced to finish his best-selling memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Few people know the cottage is here in Saratoga County, 30 miles
north of Albany and two miles west of Northway Exit 16. Where it
once sat in the shadow of the grand Balmoral Hotel, it now has Mt.
McGregor Correctional Facility as a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, all is as it was in the days following Grant's death.
Personal effects, medicine bottles, even the original floral
arrangements from his funeral provide a look into the 18th
president's last weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Grant was literally fighting his last great battle here,''
said Kathleen Cummings, a member of the Friends of Grant Cottage, a
group that cares for the two-story mountain retreat and provides
educational tours during the summer. ''He was desperate to get his
memoirs done.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting fleeced by corrupt financier Ferdinand Ward in
1884, Grant was broke. At the urging of Mark Twain, the ailing
Grant determined to write his memoirs to help restore his family's
name and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was his last battle and he won it,'' said Richard
Trombley, who portrays Grant at re-enactments. Strikingly familiar,
Trombley bore the president's characteristic graying whiskers, silk
top hat, Prince Albert coat, house slippers and ivory muffler, worn
to warm his ravaged throat. ''In death, he was able to do for his
family what he was unable to do in life: Provide for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Trombley was surrounded by other re-enactors Sunday, including
the president's wife, Julia, his children and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Grant's death in 1885, veterans of the Grand
Army of the Republic, the men who served him as he led Union troops
to victory in the Civil War, ascended the Adirondack foothill,
encamped and posted an honor guard at the remains of their leader.
</P>
<P>
   Now, exactly 115 years later, descendants of those men stood in
dappled sunlight and lifted anew the mantle borne by their
grandfathers' fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We stopped and stood for a moment and I looked at my watch and
it was the exact minute,'' said Daniel T. Cole, a member of the
Sons of Union Veterans of the Civil War Camp 154.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's maternal great-great-grandfather, George Thomas Hatch,
fought with Grant under his first command. His paternal
great-great-grandfather, Joel Cole, was under Grant when Robert E.
Lee surrendered April 9, 1865 at Appomattox Court House.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rave's great-great-grandfather, Charles Kniffin, fought in
places like Bull Run, Antietam, Fredericksburg and Gettysburg,
where he would lose his leg.
</P>
<P>
   It is for their ancestors - and all those who fought in that
great, terrible war - that men like Cole and Rave and groups like
the Friends of Grant Cottage exist, they say. Children get a few
pages in a history book but most fail to take advantage of living
histories that remain in places like Grant Cottage.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the cottage, a stone sits. Across the top of its
verdigris plaque is a message: ''Lest We Forget.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here to keep green the memories,'' said Rave. ''We're
honoring our ancestors who stood here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://saints.css.edu/mkelsey/cottage.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.suvcw.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
