<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sick baby seal found on Jones Beach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WANTAGH, N.Y. (AP) - A baby seal found at Jones Beach State Park
was being treated Sunday for dehydration and malnourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Workers from the Theodore Roosevelt Nature Center found the sick
hooded seal pup at West End Field 2 on Saturday while monitoring
local nests of birds known as plovers, the Riverhead Foundation for
Marine Research and Preservation said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Durham, a stranding expert from the Riverhead
Foundation, examined the 3-foot, 45-pound male pup and found he was
dehydrated and malnourished. The animal, named Plover by his
rescuers, will be given fluids and monitored closely for several
days, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Plover was believed to be two to three months old. Hooded seals
are generally found on ice drifts off the east coast of Canada and
along the coast of Greenland, but they have been known to swim
south along the U.S. eastern seaboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
