<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dragila Beats Own Pole Vault Record  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Stacy Dragila smashed her world pole
vault record Sunday, clearing 15 feet, 2&AMP;frac14; inches, at the U.S.
Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila had set the previous record of 15-1&AMP;frac34; at Phoenix in May.
</P>
<P>
   The former rodeo performer and heptathlete won the inaugural
world indoor championship in 1997 and the inaugural world outdoor
title last year. She is the favorite for the inaugural pole vault
gold medal at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   After soaring over the record height, Dragila had the bar raised
to 15-5, but she missed three times. Her best attempt was her
second, when the bar hung up momentarily after she cleared it, but
it fell when Dragila apparently nicked it on the way down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
