<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, July 23, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Returns to Camp David
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- Hurrying back from an abbreviated trip to Asia,
President Clinton rejoined troubled Middle East talks at Camp David today,
saying ''I'm keeping my fingers crossed'' for a peace deal. Clinton arrived by
helicopter at the presidential retreat, where aides said his first order of
business would be to meet with his own negotiating team and then assess the
state of the summit. On a 13th day of talks -- the same period required to
strike a deal at the landmark 1978 Camp David summit -- neither Israel nor the
Palestinians signaled any change in position on the prime point of dispute:
Jerusalem. Both sides claim the ancient city as their capital.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colo. Fires Uncover Native Dwellings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MESA VERDE NATIONAL PARK, Colo. (AP) -- More than a hundred years after
cowboys first discovered the native American dwellings in the cliffs of Mesa
Verde National Park, a wildfire raging through the area is uncovering more sites
and giving archaeologists a better understanding of the people who used to live
here. At least a dozen previously unknown sites have been found as the latest
wildfire stripped away concealing vegetation. The blaze had charred 8,000 acres
as of today and was only 15 percent contained.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Children Released From Hostage Standoff
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A murder suspect holding five hostages in a suburban
home released two of the four children today as police tried to end the two-day
standoff. Both children, an 8-year-old boy and a girl under 1, were in good
health, although the boy was hungry and thirsty, Orange County Sheriff Kevin
Beary said. Beary said the suspect, Jamie Dean Petron, 41, had asked police to
see the children reunited with their parents on live television after releasing
them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cheney Said Sanguine on VP Chances
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush's top vice presidential candidate, former
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, has told associates there is a good chance he
will get the job, officials said today as the Republican governor from Texas
prepared to announce his pick. Cheney, former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri and
perhaps others are on Bush's short list, according to highly placed GOP
officials. In seclusion at his Texas ranch, Bush tentatively planned to
introduce his running mate Tuesday. Even his closest advisers said they did not
know if he had made up his mind today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Backs FDA Check of Cholestin
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration should be allowed to regulate
a dietary supplement made from a substance that is chemically identical to the
active ingredient in a drug that lowers cholesterol, an appeals court has ruled.
The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Friday that a federal court in Utah
erred when it said the FDA could not regulate the dietary supplement Cholestin.
The FDA had banned imports of red yeast powder containing mevinolin, which is
used to make Cholestin. Because mevinolin is identical to a synthetic drug --
sold as Mevacor and prescribed to lower cholesterol -- the agency regarded the
powder as an unapproved drug.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
American Airlines Pilots Reach Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- AMR Corp.'s American Airlines and its pilots union
have reportedly agreed to a tentative deal that would extend the union's
contract and wipe out a $45.5 million debt to the airline. The Allied Pilots
Association and the airline both said they reached an agreement, but they didn't
provide details. The Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported today that the union and
airline agreed to extend the contract for one year. The deal also includes an
agreement to eliminate the union's $45.5 million debt to the airline for a
sickout in February 1999 over a pilot dispute, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tiger Woods Completes Career Grand Slam
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- Tiger Woods stepped into history today, winning
the British open with a 19-under 269, the lowest score in relation to par ever
at a major championship. It was a fitting way for Woods to win at the home of
golf, making him the youngest player ever to complete the career Grand Slam.
Woods becomes only the fifth player to win all four majors, the first since Jack
Nicklaus won the 1966 British Open.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Johnson Wins 200 Meters Semifinal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- In the most anticipated showdown in track and
field in three years, Michael Johnson shook off a tender right quadriceps and
defeated trash-talking adversary Maurice Greene in the 200-meter semifinals at
the U.S. Olympic trials today. The meeting was to be replayed tonight, when
Johnson and Greene met in the final. The first round of this heavyweight battle
of the world's top two sprinters went to Johnson. He swept across the finish
line in 20.14 seconds, finishing second behind former NCAA champion John Capel,
with Greene third at 20.30. The top three advanced to the final.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
	    
</SUBHEAD>
