<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Captain Steve Wins Swaps Stakes  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert was facing a bad
ending to a trying week until Captain Steve salvaged things with a
2&AMP;frac12;-length victory over Tiznow in the $500,000 Swaps Stakes on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's week hadn't exactly gone well before he saddled
Captain Steve at Hollywood Park. First, he was hit with a lawsuit
for allegedly over-racing 1998 Kentucky Derby winner Real Quiet,
then one of his horses tested positive for morphine.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday got off to a disappointing start when his horses running
in Delaware and Texas both lost, including Silverbulletday in the
Delaware Handicap. Captain Steve improved Baffert's outlook with a
strong kick in the stretch to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God he's back,'' Baffert said. ''I needed this race
really, really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert faces a hearing with stewards at Del Mar later this week
over Nautical Look's positive test. The lawsuit, filed by Highland
Stud of Paris, Ky., over the handling of Real Quiet, also accuses
Baffert of defrauding the farm out of $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''That other stuff, we don't worry about that. We just worry
about the horses,'' he said of his troubles. ''That guy is trying
to fight Mike (Pegram) in the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Pegram sold Real Quiet to Highland
Stud before the colt won the Derby, but Pegram was allowed to
continue racing Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, who proved a bust in the Kentucky Derby (eighth)
and Preakness (fourth), became the third horse to win the Hollywood
Futurity and the Swaps.
</P>
<P>
   The colt won the Futurity on the same track last December, but
he bruised his feet early this year and Baffert said he hadn't been
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now he's put his weight back and he's enjoying it. He's a
different horse,'' he said. ''I was going to be so disappointed if
he didn't win. It was time to fish or cut bait.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Swaps win for Baffert, Pegram and jockey Corey
Nakatani. Captain Steve's human namesake was on hand, too. Capt.
Steve Thompson of the Louisville, Ky., Police Department, who
proved a huge hit during Derby Week, traveled west for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve covered 1[ miles in 1:48 under co-high weight of
120 pounds. He paid $3.80, $2.40 and $2.10 as the wagering
favorite. The victory, worth $300,000, increased Captain Steve's
career earnings to more than $1.4 million, with six wins in 15
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow returned $2.80 and $2.20, while Spacelink was another
length back in third and paid $2.40 to show.
</P>
<P>
   Riding Captain Steve for the first time, Nakatani settled the
colt off the rail behind leader Millencolin, then went between
horses into the second turn and took a brief lead before unleashing
a strong stretch kick.
</P>
<P>
   ''Turning for home, I couldn't have been any happier. I had a
lot of horse under me and I was just sitting here biding my time,''
Nakatani said. ''When I set him down, he just kicked away from the
other horse (Tiznow). I think he's going to be able to get better
off of this effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve was coming off a win in the Iowa Derby on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew the trip to Iowa was really going to help. He needed a
confidence builder. I needed to get a win under his belt,'' said
Baffert, who is considering the Haskell, Travers, Jim Dandy, West
Virginia Derby or Remington Derby for Captain Steve's next race.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Espinoza, who already clinched his first Hollywood Park
riding title with one day left in the meeting, struggled with
Tiznow on the backside.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to strangle down on him harder that I would have wanted.
Then I had plenty of room on the inside, but when I decided to go,
he stayed in the same place,'' he said. ''I could see the leader
had too much left. I only rode hard for second after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey Memo was fourth, Millencolin fifth and Spicy Stuff, also
trained by Baffert, was last in the six-horse field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
