<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Guatemalans Trapped In Trailer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Gaspar Juarez Mendoza was one of 40
Guatemalans hidden among sacks of corn in the back of a truck that
was supposed to secret them across Mexico to the U.S. border -- and
a better life.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his journey ended in tragedy when the trailer carrying
him and his companions was abandoned Saturday in the blistering
midday sun along a highway in southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   By the time one of the occupants managed to pry open the doors
10 hours later, all 40 were suffering from severe dehydration, and
many had already passed out.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Tobasco state found the Guatemalans sprawled out along
the highway, Red Cross officials said. Juarez Mendoza, whose age
was not immediately known, was one of seven who had to be
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   He died later Saturday at a hospital in Villahermosa, 410 miles
southeast of Mexico City, the government news agency Notimex
reported Saturday night. The six others remain in serious
condition, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We couldn't breathe,'' one of the Guatemalans, Juventino
Arango, told The Associated Press. ''We were buried among the sacks
of corn. I had to break them open and empty them so I could get out
and ask for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Those hospitalized were suffering from severe kidney damage due
to dehydration, and also complications from asphyxiation, said Dr.
Heriberto Tosca.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors said they had left two weeks ago, making their way to
San Cristobal de las Casas in the Mexican state of Chiapas, which
borders Guatemala. In Chiapas, they hired a smuggler and paid him
$1,500 to take them to the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tragic end to their journey, those who came out
relatively unscathed said they planned to keep trying to enter the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course we'll try again,'' said one of the Guatemalans.
''Even if the heat kills us or we drown, we will keep on trying
because in our country there is no way to live.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, 22 bodies washed ashore after a boat carrying
Guatemalans trying to reach the United States sank off Mexico's
Pacific coast. The lone survivor told the government news agency
that he and the others had boarded the boat before dawn near the
Mexico-Guatemala border and were caught by a storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 2014 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
