<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Don't say 'Yuck,' Hudson River swimming studied  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTLETON-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. (AP) - On hot summer days, teen-agers
here will amble past a No Trespassing sign, walk over the railroad
tracks and jump in the cloudy waters of the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The young swimmers swear the water is warm, refreshing and
reasonably clean. Just don't try telling that to Heidi Herholz, a
resident of this Albany-area river village who scoffs at the idea
of diving in.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to catch a disease,'' she said, ''or come out
glowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are the attitudes New York state faces as it considers
creating more public swimming spots along the Hudson River.
Although the river is getting cleaner, old opinions linger. Also,
the state is faced with finding swimming spots on a shoreline where
public access is limited by railroad tracks and private homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration has paid a consulting firm $88,000 to
study the feasibility of creating more public swimming spots,
focusing on the 140 miles between Manhattan and Troy. Environmental
groups and residents have been polled on potential spots. And two
public meetings are being held in the river valley this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe the time is right,'' said state Environmental
Commissioner John Cahill. ''The water quality in the Hudson River
has improved dramatically over the past decade.''
</P>
<P>
   He ought to know. Cahill annually takes part in a three-mile
swim across the river north of New York City for charity. And his
agency, the state Department of Environmental Conservation, has
classified the river as swimmable from northern Columbia County to
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hudson is haunted by its past. Back in the '60's, the
river was infamous for running with raw sewage and factory wastes.
Marine life was choked out of some areas for lack of oxygen. There
was a joke back then about a drunk who fell off a boat into the
Hudson and had to be dusted off.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Clean Water Act of 1972 and later state
environmental programs are credited with reducing toxic discharges
and turning the tide.
</P>
<P>
   The river is still not the pure waterway Henry Hudson sailed up
in 1609. Upper river silt still contains traces of polychlorinated
biphenyls - or PCBs - and state health officials advise limiting
consumption of fish from the river.
</P>
<P>
   But the swimming is good, said Hudson River Sloop Clearwater
executive director Andy Mele, who has swum the Hudson over a
hundred times.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never heard of a single soul getting ill or getting a
festering cut,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mele said he gets calls every summer asking if the water is
safe. He tells callers yes, but offers a caveat: Avoid swimming for
a few days after heavy rains to avoid sewage runoff from old
treatment plants. And he adds: ''I really wouldn't go out of my way
to swim in New York Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   The knottier question along the Hudson River is not whether if
you can swim, but where you can swim.
</P>
<P>
   Boaters can just dive from the sides of crafts. The kids in
Castleton make do with an old earthen pier. But public swimming
spots are rare. Croton Point in Westchester County and Kingston
Point in Ulster County are among the few.
</P>
<P>
   A big problem is that rail lines run near the Hudson's eastern
shore from New York City to the Albany area. There are stretches of
track on the river's western shore too. Beyond that, prime
riverside real estate is in private hands. Cahill said river access
plans in past decades didn't consider swimming because the water
was too dirty.
</P>
<P>
   Rockland County-based consultants Lawler, Matusky &AMP; Skelly
Engineers will conduct the two-year study to identify possible
sites for beach development. The firm will also address tactics for
water quality improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The study is part of the Hudson River Estuary Action Plan
released by Gov. George Pataki in 1996. Pataki, who grew up in
Peekskill near the river, has already overseen the creation of new
waterfront trails and new boat launches.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the popularity of boating on the river, Cahill said:
''Hopefully, in five to 10 years you'll say there's a lot of
swimming on the river as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-23-00 2038 </TRAILER>
