<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police: Man shoots 2, leads cop on chase, then kills self  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OAKDALE, N.Y. (AP) - A man who may have been angry because he
believed his daughter was assaulted shot her alleged attacker and
another person Sunday, then led police on a highway chase that
ended with his suicide, Suffolk County police said.
</P>
<P>
   William Mosca, 43, of Sound Beach, forced his way into an
Oakdale home demanding to see one of its occupants, police said. He
fired 15 shots with a semiautomatic handgun, and hit two of the
four people inside, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were Daniel Dellapina, 16, and Gregory Malfer, 25,
who both lived in the house. Malfer allegedly attacked Mosca's
daughter, Mackenzie Mosca, several months ago, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives were investigating the possibility that Mosca was
seeking revenge for the alleged assault, police said. It was not
immediately known whether a complaint had been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Mosca fled the shooting scene by motorcycle, and was soon being
followed by four police cars, which chased him west on the Northern
State Parkway, police said. He allegedly turned around in an effort
to elude police, and pointed his gun at them without firing.
</P>
<P>
   Mosca lost control of his motorcycle around 11:20 a.m. while
trying to pull onto the highway's shoulder east of Route 231 in Dix
Hills, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers ordered him to drop the gun he was pointing at them,
but instead he shot himself in the head, they said. He was
pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Malfer and Dellapina were airlifted to the University Medical
Center at Stony Brook. Police did not know their condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
