<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   GURNEE, Ill. (AP) -- Nancy Lopez's search for a U.S.
Women's Open
championship is far from over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Women's Open is the only major to elude the 43-year-old LPGA
Hall of Famer. She's finished second four times, including 1997
when she became the only person to shoot four rounds in the 60s at
the Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   She barely made it to the weekend this year after missing her
last two Women's Open cuts, and finished tied for 46th at 14-over
302. But she didn't think her game was far off after shooting a
1-over 73 in Sunday's final round.
</P>
<P>
   ''This week I felt real good about my game, I was hitting the
ball very well,'' Lopez said. ''I putted just terribly the first
three days, and finally today I made putts -- a lot of them were for
pars, but at least I made them. If I just have an average of 30
putts every day I should be right in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez received a special exemption from the U.S. Golf
Association, sparing her from having to qualify for her 24th
Women's Open. But she said she would go through qualifying if she
had to next year.
</P>
<P>
   Anything not to miss a Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hoping I can win something before I have to qualify, if I
have to,'' Lopez said. ''I just have to keep working because I know
that I've got some wins in my bag still. I feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez's best finish this year in eight LPGA tournaments was a
tie for ninth in The LPGA Office Depot, her first event of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   KING OF PAIN: Timing was the most painful part of Betsy King's
back injury.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time U.S. Women's Open champion was playing in the last
group Saturday and was just one stroke off the lead when she
strained a muscle in her lower back. Hurting on every swing and
barely able to continue, King shot a 10-over 82 and fell out of
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of scary,'' King said. ''One second I'm a shot out
and then one swing later It was more of a shock than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   King fared better Sunday, shooting a 79 to finish tied for 46th
at 14 over.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to play even though she knew there was no way she
could be competitive with her injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're playing against the world's best golfers, my swing
was like a 10-handicapper,'' King said. ''That's basically what I
was the last two days. It was tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, she played the last five holes in two under.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess it's like any 10-handicapper, eventually you hit a few
good shots,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   King received treatment for her back after Saturday's round, and
was given medicine by her dad, a retired doctor, that left her
feeling ''woozy'' during her round Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Though she joked that part of the incentive for playing was a
paycheck, her main motivation was the tournament itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be a shot out of the lead (Saturday) and then make nothing
of the week, I just couldn't stand that,'' King said. ''If it had
been a regular event I probably wouldn't have played, but because
it was the Open I just wanted to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   NATIONS COLLIDE: There was a welcome site for Karrie Webb when
she reached the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to a gallery that was squarely on the side of
American Meg Mallon for most of the day, suddenly Webb came upon a
family holding a large Australian flag.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to clam myself down. I got some tears in my eyes because
I felt like I was playing the Solheim Cup out there and I was on
the European team,'' Webb said. ''It was a great sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallon joked that she was trying to take advantage of the
gallery's tendency to root for Americans, saying that's why she
wore a white shirt with thin blue and red stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was wearing my stripes today. I was trying anything,''
Mallon said. ''It was a neat feeling. People were really cheering
me on.''
</P>
<P>
   SORENSTAM SETBACK: Two-time U.S. Women's Open champion Annika
Sorenstam was considered a favorite coming into this week, winning
her last two LPGA tournaments and four of her last six.
</P>
<P>
   She was never in the hunt after opening rounds of 73 and 75.
</P>
<P>
   ''A major is so much more than just playing well coming into the
tournament. I think I showed that,'' Sorenstam said. ''I played
really well coming into here and I'm not even on even on the
leaderboard. So it just shows what a major means.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam did pick up another top-10 finish, though, shooting a
final-round 70 to finish tied for ninth at 3-over 291.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked my caddie (Terry McNamara), I said, 'How do you play
this course?,''' Sorenstam said. ''He said, 'You're playing it the
right way. We just need some good breaks and to make some of the
crucial putts.' And that's the difference. I have not played bad
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   With her win, Webb tied Sorenstam for most victories on the LPGA
Tour this year with five.
</P>
<P>
   ALL IN THE FAMILY: The Wongluekiet twins have a knack for
major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Naree Wongluekiet, a 14-year-old who just finished eighth grade,
won low amateur honors at the U.S. Women's Open, finishing tied for
40th at 12-over 300. Her twin sister, Aree, was low amateur earlier
this year at the Nabisco Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''It feels really nice to know my sister did it at Nabisco and
now me here,'' Naree said. ''My first goal was to make the cut and
after that my goal was to be low amateur.''
</P>
<P>
   Naree has an exemption for one more LPGA event this year, and
says she will take a lot from her Open experience with her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I learned a lot this week,'' she said. ''I learned that you
have to trust yourself and that when I get out here, I'm going to
have a caddie, so I have to trust the caddie.''
</P>
<P>
   DRAWING A CROWD: Sunday's final round of the U.S. Women's Open
drew a gallery of 25,409, the largest of the week. Including the
practice rounds and pro-am, the tournament drew 101,568.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
