<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rome's Colosseum Now a Concert Hall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Rome's 19-century-old Colosseum debuted as a concert
hall Sunday, its newly renovated stage serving as the starlit venue
for the premiere of a Sicilian composer's work dedicated to Mother
Theresa.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Francesco Rutelli was among a black-tie crowd of more than
300 at the first and only scheduled performance of Franco Mannino's
Missa Solemnis.
</P>
<P>
   The concert was the first on the ancient arena's reconstructed
stage. African instruments, including elephant tusks, blended
Sunday night with the classic elements of Rome's Teatro dell'Opera
orchestra and instruments from Asia, Europe and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Missa aims to bring together the diverse cultures in one
long embrace,'' said Mannino, who conducted the opening movement
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Completed in A.D. 80, the Colosseum once seated 45,000
spectators, who watched gladiators doing battle -- and, according to
tradition, lions consuming Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Falling into disuse in the fifth century with the decline of the
Roman Empire, it has remained one of Rome's best-known landmarks.
The Colosseum reopened for public entertainment earlier this month
with a performance of the classical Greek tragedy Oedipus Rex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
