<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJohn Coert Campbell:
<TEXT>
<P>
   COHASSET, Mass. (AP) -- John Coert Campbell, a former member of
the State Department's policy planning council and expert author on
Middle Eastern and Eastern European affairs, died July 16. He was
88.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was a consultant and adviser to the State Department
from 1963 to 1980 and a member of its policy planning council in
1967 during the Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   He also served on an advisory panel for the State Department's
Bureau of Near East and South Asian Affairs during the 1960s. He
was a State Department specialist in Eastern Europe from 1942 to
1946 and officer in charge of Balkan affairs and a member of the
policy planning staff from 1949 to 1955.
</P>
<P>
   As a staff member of the New York-based Council on Foreign
Relations for 27 years, he provided analyses of world affairs.
Johannes Dyba:
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Archbishop Johannes Dyba, considered one of
Germany's most conservative clergymen for his outspoken views
against abortion and domestic partnerships, died Saturday of heart
failure. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   Dyba, who was archbishop of the Fulda diocese in central Germany
and the Roman Catholic bishop for the military, polarized Germans
and caused controversy within the church with his often pointed
comments on questions of morality.
</P>
<P>
   He was ordained in 1959 in Cologne and after a short time
serving in churches went to study in Rome. He served the Vatican in
diplomatic posts in Buenos Aires, Argentina; The Hague,
Netherlands; Kinshasa, Congo, and Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1983, he was named the head of the Fulda diocese,
and in 1990 also became the Catholic military bishop, visiting
German troops on missions in Yugoslavia and elsewhere.
Cenk Koray:
</P>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Cenk Koray, a Turkish television host and
journalist, died Sunday of a heart attack, news reports said. He
was 56.
</P>
<P>
   Koray amused Turkish TV audiences during much of the 1970s and
1980s with his wit and humor as host of entertainment and game
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Koray trained as a lawyer but chose journalism as a career
instead. His lucky break came when he was asked to stand in for
another popular TV presenter who was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, Koray had been writing a column for the
daily newspaper Aksam and was the spokesman for his favorite soccer
team, Istanbul's Besiktas, until last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-23-00 2111 </TRAILER>
