<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   It's never easy to replace a legend, as the Miami
Dolphins are
discovering in their search for a starting quarterback.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The team finished its 52-play controlled scrimmage Sunday at
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., much like it started the day -- unsure who
will take over for Dan Marino, the future Hall of Famer who retired
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The two quarterbacks vying for the No. 1 job, Damon Huard and
Jay Fiedler, split time Sunday with similar results. Each threw a
touchdown pass and an interception.
</P>
<P>
   Huard was 7-for-10 for 50 yards, including a 34-yard scoring
toss to Robert Baker on a post pattern. Fiedler moved the team more
effectively early on, going 5-for-8 for 63 yards, including a
29-yard touchdown strike to Lamar Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The quarterbacks threw two interceptions and we can't survive
doing that,'' coach Dave Wannstedt said.
</P>
<P>
   Huard gave himself a C-minus grade. Working against Miami's
first-string defense, he threw an interception on his first attempt
</P>
<P>
   Neither quarterback gained an edge in their competition, said
offensive coordinator Chan Gailey, the former Dallas Cowboys head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   They ''probably did some good and some bad things,'' Gailey
said. ''That's the best way to (assess) it without seeing game
film.''
Panthers:
</P>
<P>
   Reggie White, the NFL's career sacks leader, signed a contract
with Carolina on Sunday after arriving at the team's training camp
at Spartanburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   White, 38, who passed a physical in Charlotte on Friday, was to
work with strength and conditioning coach Jerry Simmons on Monday,
rather than participating in the regular team practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''We look forward to having Reggie White on our football team,''
coach George Seifert said. ''He brings a special talent and special
mindset that we believe will help in our development as a team.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert has said he hopes White will be ready to play by the
third preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers offered White a five-year contract worth about $20
million -- although White said he may only play one year -- with
several performance incentives based on Carolina's defensive
improvement.
Seahawks:
</P>
<P>
   Sean Dawkins, released last month because of salary-cap
restraints, has agreed to rejoin Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have agreed to things,'' coach and general manager Mike
Holmgren said Sunday. ''I expect him in the next day or two. ...
I'm glad Sean decided to come on back. He makes this a better
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the signing were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Dawkins caught 58 passes for 992 yards last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have only first-round draft choice Chris McIntosh,
an offensive lineman from Wisconsin, still unsigned.
Vikings:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hovan, the Minnesota Vikings' first-round draft pick, was
the only player who didn't show up for the start of training camp
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hovan's agents spent the day meeting with team officials, but a
deal couldn't be reached in time, coach Dennis Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been in the NFL for a long period of time. Each
individual guy has to get what he considers a fair deal,'' Green
said. ''We're negotiating. We think we know what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovan, an All-America from Boston College who can play nose
tackle, defensive end and defensive tackle, will be expected to
contribute immediately to the Vikings' revamped defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 305-pound Hovan will help fill the void created by
the departures of Duane Clemons, Jerry Ball and Chris Doleman, who
combined for 19 sacks in 1999. Clemons signed with Kansas City, and
Ball and Doleman retired.
Redskins:
</P>
<P>
   Amid mouthfuls of ''scornbread'' and ''drop-the-ball baked
beans,'' the former home of the Redskins' training camp, Frostburg
State University, held its annual picnic for a team that wasn't
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins recently broke a 10-year contract with the
university by moving their preseason training camp after only five
years. The team became the first in NFL history to charge admission
to preseason practices at the new camp in Ashburn, Va.	   In Frostburg, Md.,
about 130 people showed up Saturday for this
year's Jack-Kent-Cooke-Out, named for the late Redskins owner,
which featured a tongue-in-cheek menu: ''scornbread and butter,''
''Fan-friendly Fruit Salad (No sour grapes),'' and ''Iced Tea (Not
bitter. Really, it's not.)''
</P>
<P>
   A state study last year estimated that the Redskins brought $2.9
million to the town.
Buccaneers:
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson was among the first players arriving when Tampa
Bay reported to training camp Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's pretty much the way I go about doing things,'' said the
two-time Pro Bowl wide receiver, who was obtained in an offseason
trade with the New York Jets. ''I'm just here to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers on Sunday agreed to terms on four-year contract
with guard Cosey Coleman, the team's second-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Coleman, Tampa Bay released long snapper Mitch
Palmer. The Bucs also signed tight end Patrick Hape to a $385,000,
one-year contract.
Bears:
</P>
<P>
   Second-round draft pick Mike Brown ended his holdout Sunday,
signing a four-year deal. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the 39th overall pick in April's NFL draft, left Nebraska
as the second-leading tackler in school history and had nine career
interceptions.
Saints:
</P>
<P>
   Guard Chris Naeole sprained a ligament in his left knee in a
hard fall late in the ''Black &AMP; Gold Scrimmage'' on Saturday, and
was helped off the field. Tests Sunday indicated the ligament was
not torn.
</P>
<P>
   There is no word on how long he will be out of practice. Naeole
injured the same knee during his rookie season.
</P>
</TEXT>
