Johnson, Greene Both Pull Up Lame
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- In the most anticipated showdown in track and
field in three years, Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene both pulled up lame in
the final of the 200 meters at the U.S. Olympic trials today. The hugely hyped
meeting was held twice because both were in the same semifinal heat, then came
back less than two hours later in the final. Going into the race, Johnson was
nursing a tender right quadriceps, but it was his left quadriceps that forced
him to quit about 80 meters into the race. It was evident that when Johnson came
out of the blocks, he wasn't healthy.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
