<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-23 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Hits Islands Off Tokyo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A strong earthquake shook a string of volcanic
islands off Tokyo on Monday, the Meteorological Agency said. There
were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Meteorological Agency said the magnitude 5.5 earthquake hit
the Izu islands chain at 6:52 a.m. and was centered at a shallow
point beneath the seabed near the islands of Niijima and Kozushima.
</P>
<P>
   Takashi Makino, a municipal official on Niijima, home to around
600 people, said there were no immediate reports of damage or
injuries, but officials were checking roads and other sparsely
populated islands.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was most strongly felt on Niijima, about 105 miles,
south of Tokyo. Kozushima, with a population of around 2,300, is
located about 12 miles south of Niijima.
</P>
<P>
   A quake of magnitude 5 can cause damage to homes if it occurs in
a residential area.
</P>
<P>
   The Meteorological Agency said there might be a ''slight''
change in sea levels from the quake, but no damage was expected.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a quake of magnitude 5.0 jolted Niijima and
neighboring small islands but no damage or injuries were reported.
On July 1, a magnitude 6.4 earthquake killed a man on Kozushima.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's quake was among thousands that have hit the small
islands in recent weeks. A total of 1,129 were registered on Sunday
alone, with about 20 percent of them strong enough to be felt. As
of 9 a.m. Monday, 491 tremors were registered, with 148 them strong
enough to be felt, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most earthquake-prone nations as it
sits atop four tectonic plates, slabs of land that move across the
earth's surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
