<HEADLINE> Bills Sign Rookie DE Erik Flowers  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFORD, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Bills signed rookie defensive
end Erik Flowers on Sunday, the last of the team's eight draft
picks to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not released.
</P>
<P>
   ''It feels great,'' Flowers told Empire Sports Network after
arriving at Rochester International Airport on Sunday evening. ''I
was talking to (a Bills' teammate) yesterday and he was telling me
he was having a blast up here. I'm like, 'Man, I got to hurry up
and get out of here.' And plus the heat in Texas is ridiculous, so
I'm happy to get out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team management nor Eric Metz, Flowers' agent who flew
into town over the weekend to negotiate the deal personally, could
be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, the 26th pick in April's draft, arrived at the Bills'
new training camp at St. John Fisher College in time for the 7 p.m.
team meeting. After missing the first three days of practice, he
will take part in Monday morning's session.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers led Arizona State with 10 sacks last season while also
recording 68 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   The signing was critical for the Bills, trying to shore up the
sagging right side of the defensive line. Bruce Smith, the team's
career sack leader, signed as a free agent with Washington last
February. Marcellus Wiley, Smith's successor, will miss at least
two more weeks recovering from back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers became the Bills' first defensive end to be drafted in
the first round since the team took Smith first overall in 1985.
Flowers was also the first rookie holdout in general manager John
Butler's eight-year term.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of camp, Bills coach Wade Phillips raised concerns
that Flowers was missing critical development time with every
practice he missed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
